<HEADLINE> AL Hopes UN General Assembly to Get Tough on </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, March 12 (Xinhua) -- A draft resolution under debate at
the U.N. General Assembly today could serve as a very tough
condemnation of the Israeli construction of Jewish settlements in
East Jerusalem, an Arab League (AL) official said here today.
</P>
<P>
Assistant Secretary General for Arab Affairs Ambassador Ahmed
Ben Helli told the Egyptian MENA news agency that the Arab call to
halt the construction of Jewish settlements enjoys wide support
among the 185-member U.N. General Assembly.
</P>
<P>
The U.S., Israel's biggest ally and sponsor of the peace
process, last Friday vetoed the European-sponsored draft
resolution against Israeli plans to build 6,500 Jewish homes in
Har Homa, a tree-covered hill in Arab East Jerusalem. The
resolution was supported by 14 other U.N. Security Council members.
</P>
<P>
The Arab and non-aligned groups at the U.N. then turned the
matter to the General Assembly, where a similar resolution is
certain to win overwhelming backing. Regarded as the gauge of
international opinion, however, the assembly's resolutions do not
carry the weight of the Security Council resolutions and are
non-abiding.
</P>
<P>
"Israeli officials have to realize that the Arabs have options
that could strongly defend their legitimate rights that are also
supported by the international community," said the official.
</P>
<P>
The Arab position and determination will not to be bargained
with, he added.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, he warned that Israel's continued intransigence will
push the region into the vicious circle of violence and prompt
Arab countries to reexamine their positions towards Israel.
</P>
<P>
"Some Arab countries have already halted steps towards
normalization with Israel because of its settlement policy and
violation of peace agreements," he added.
</P>
<P>
Commenting on the U.S. stance, the official said that
Washington realizes it has joint interests with the Arab world,
which "are buttressed with the realization of a just and
comprehensive Mideast peace."
</P>
<P>
In fact, U.S. guarantees of the return of all Arab lands
occupied by Israel since 1967 were part of the principles of the
1991 Madrid peace conference co-sponsored by the U.S. and Russia,
he added.
</P>
<P>
In a statement issued Sunday, the AL said the U.S. veto runs
contrary to the U.S. letters of guarantees relayed to the
Palestinian side at Madrid. The letter says that no change would
be made on the demographic features of Jerusalem until "final
status" talks.
</P>
<P>
Both Israelis and Palestinians want to build the capital of
their states in Jerusalem, the holy place of Judaism, Christianity
and Islam. As the final talks drawing near, Jerusalem has become
the butt of Israeli-Palestinian tug of war. 
</P>
</TEXT>
