<HEADLINE> Algeria Regulates Self-Defense Groups' Activity </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, March 12 (Xinhua) -- The Algerian government has
recently published a decree to regulate the activity of the
country's 200,000-strong self-defense groups, called Patriots,
which are organized by civilians to fight Islamic militants.
</P>
<P>
The Agence France-Presse (AFP) quoted the decree, which
appeared in an official daily, as saying that the self-defense
groups are from now on officially called Groups of Legitimate
Defense (GLD).
</P>
<P>
The decree said that each team of the GLD, manned by "volunteer
citizens" and "duly authorized by the public powers," is headed by
a leader or by an agent of security forces who reside in the area
where the group carries out its self-defense duties.
</P>
<P>
It said that the creation of a GLD team should be authorized by
the local prefect, requested by the local residents and agreed
upon by the security forces.
</P>
<P>
The members of the GLD are entitled to take "action of
counter-attack, as individuals or in an organized way, against all
aggression, acts of terrorism or subversion, or in a general way,
against all acts of organized criminality or delinquency conducted
against people or properties."
</P>
<P>
The GLD members are also required to "prevent or repel acts of
terrorism and subversion against places of residence, places of
social life, as well as public and social infrastructure
equipment."
</P>
<P>
The decree said that the GLD members cannot "penetrate the
interior of a home or a closed space except in cases of
entrenchment or necessity to bring rescues at the appeal of
others."
</P>
<P>
The GLD members are not paid or compensated by the government
unless a member cannot "exercise normally his professional
activity because of charges in (carrying out) legitimate defense
(duties)," said the decree.
</P>
<P>
The first groups of self-defense teams appeared in 1994 in the
villages of Kabylie, and the number of such groups has increased
over the past three years in areas where Islamic militants are
active. 
</P>
</TEXT>
