<HEADLINE> S. Africa's 1997/98 Budget Unveiled </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, March 12 (Xinhua) -- South Africa's 1997/98
budget was unveiled today by Finance Minister Trevor Manuel in
Cape Town, spelling out some new economic and financial measures
for the new fiscal year which starts in April.
</P>
<P>
Highlights of the new budget included significant relaxation
of foreign exchange controls, tax relief package of low and
middle income earners, individuals allowed to invest limited
funds abroad and hold foreign currency accounts in local banks,
and VAT (value added Tax) stays unchanged at 14 percent.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, some customs duties for certain imported goods will
come down, but alcohol and cigarettes will become more expensive,
and fuel price remains unchanged.
</P>
<P>
In his first budget speech, currently televized live
nationwide, Manuel said, however, budgeted expenditure for the
year is 186.746 billion Rand (about 41.45 billion U.S. Dollars at
present rate) and about 36 billion US Dollars revenue, leaving a
deficit of 5.5 billion US Dollars, the targeted four percent.
</P>
<P>
The 1.24 billion US Dollars education budget still takes a
significant section of the government's total spending after debt
repayments, accounting for 6.5 percent of the gross domestic
product.
</P>
<P>
The defense force will have its budget of 2.38 billion US
Dollars, a 9.4 percent decrease compared with the previous year,
while the budget for the police rises to 2.9 billion US Dollars,
a 14.4 percent increase on last year.
</P>
<P>
Expenditure for the departments of safety and security,
correctional services and justice are also up to some extent.
</P>
<P>
Describing the new fiscal year as one of consolidation, Manuel
said the government would "steer the economy firmly along the
growth path envisaged in our macro-economic strategy", released in
June last year.
</P>
<P>
He also stressed that the new budget "tells the story of a
government determined to effect deep transformation to live
within its means". 
</P>
</TEXT>
