<HEADLINE> US Poultry Export Increases Quickly in Decade </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, March 12 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. export of poultry
products increased sharply in the past 10 years, resulting mainly
from a huge import of Russia in recent years, the U.S. Journal of
Commerce reported today.
</P>
<P>
U.S. companies shipped 4.4 billion pounds of chicken products
overseas last year, totaling 2.45 billion U.S. dollars. The export
accounted for 16.9 percent of total U.S. poultry production.
</P>
<P>
It was a sharp increase compared with the export about 10 years
ago. In 1985, U.S. producers exported only 417 million pounds of
chicken products -- about 3 percent of total production, the
report said.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. export of poultry products to Russia increased quickly
since 1991, when former U.S. President George Bush granted the
country 35 million dollars in credits to buy U.S. chicken
products.
</P>
<P>
In 1996, the U.S. export of chicken leg quarters to Russia
reached 908 million dollars, nearly one fourth of total U.S.
poultry export.
</P>
<P>
The outlook of U.S. poultry export remains very strong in
coming years with many U.S. companies trying to expand market
share in the Asian countries, the paper said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
