<HEADLINE> Commentary: An American Book Aimed to Defame China (Part One) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 12 (Xinhua) -- The United States has published a
book aimed to viciously defame the People's Republic of China and
its major achievements over the past decades with sheer
fabrication and distortion of facts.
</P>
<P>
The book entitled "The Coming Conflict with America" was
published recently in the United States, in which the authors made
up a story about "China threat" and imagined military conflicts
between the United States and China in future.
</P>
<P>
The two authors of the book, Richard Bernstein and Ross
H. Munro, who were Beijing-based foreign correspondents
respectively working for Time magazine and Toronto Globe and Mail
for years, should be aware of the actual situation in China.
</P>
<P>
However, leading a secluded and comfortable life in the
diplomatic residential quarters in Beijing for years, the two were
keen to keep close contact with few so-called Chinese dissidents
rather than ordinary Chinese people.
</P>
<P>
Although the two journalists spent several years living and
working on Chinese soil, they know little about the
5,000-year-long history of Chinese civilization and turned a blind
eye to the brilliant achievements by the Chinese people in their
fight against foreign invasions and for national independence,
freedom and liberation.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, they ignored the fact that the Chinese people, under
the leadership of the Communist Party of China, overthrew the rule
by imperialists, feudal landlords and bureaucratic capitalists.
</P>
<P>
And they again turned a blind eye to the universally
acknowledged great achievements made by the Chinese people in
their reform and opening up drive for socialist modernization.
</P>
<P>
As foreigners working in China, they could neither understand
spoken Chinese nor read Chinese books. It is forgivable for them
to know little about modern China since they could not speak
Chinese and had to rely on interpreters to communicate with
Chinese people.
</P>
<P>
However in this book, the two authors racked their wits to
defame China with all sorts of anti-China materials they collected
through every means. This cannot be explained as that they have
"little learning."
</P>
<P>
Driven by a racial superiority of the "white supremacy," the
two authors are extremely domineering and conceited.
</P>
<P>
Though they witnessed the ongoing socialist construction
carried on by the Chinese people, the gradual improvement of
living standards of the Chinese people and efforts to perfect
socialist democratic and legal system in China, they furiously
imprecated and defamed China's socialist system since it did not
collapse as they wished after it happened in the Soviet Union and
East Europe.
</P>
<P>
The authors were eager to strangle China's socialist system in
the cradle.
</P>
<P>
The return of Hong Kong and Macao to China, the peaceful
reunification of the Chinese mainland and Taiwan are no doubt good
for the Chinese people.
</P>
<P>
However, the authors, viewing things with prejudice and racial
discrimination, alleged that this will break the balance of power
in the Asia-Pacific region and may even pose a challenge to the
U.S. global hegemony because it would make China more powerful.
</P>
<P>
Therefore, they concluded that these developments must be dealt
with. In their logic, only a split China is in the interests of
the United States.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970313.0012 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Commentary: An American Book Aimed to Defame China (Part Two) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Entertaining imaginary fears, the authors claimed that
Sino-U.S. confrontation is inevitable, and that conflicts of
interests between the two countries would aggravate until a war
breaks out.
</P>
<P>
Looking forward to the 21st century, the authors believed
that Sino-U.S. confrontation would be one between the top two
powers in the world because the U.S. Asia-Pacific policy in the
last hundred years has been focusing on preventing an (Asian)
power from emerging to challenge the status of the United States.
</P>
<P>
Refuting this wrong prediction to the point, Chinese Vice
Premier and Foreign Minister Qian Qichen said unless the United
States violates China's territorial integrity and sovereignty,
there would be no possibility of any occurrence of the so-called
conflicts between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
As is known to all, the United States and China were allies in
World War II and there exists no fundamental conflict of interests
between the peoples of the two countries.
</P>
<P>
The two countries used to boast effective strategic cooperation
to safeguard peace, stability, development and prosperity in the
world.
</P>
<P>
From now on, the U.S. and China, representing the world's
largest developed and developing countries respectively, share
extensive common interests.
</P>
<P>
For the sake of coming generations, the two countries have
every reason to enhance mutual trust, reduce troubles, promote
cooperation and avoid confrontation, but not a single reason to
resort to "a war."
</P>
<P>
Wishing to see a world plunged into chaos, the two authors
fabricated an "Arabian Nights"-like myth to mislead and confuse
public opinion.
</P>
<P>
They deserve the title of "loyal subjects" of the United States
of America because they always bear in mind and feel extremely
happy at their country's hegemonic acts throughout the world.
</P>
<P>
They inferred on the bases of the superpower Cold War logic
that someday China, with its rapid economic development, will
surely follow the steps of the U.S. and seek hegemony in Asia in
the future.
</P>
<P>
Cooking up a story, they claimed that driven by deep-rooted
nationalist sentiment, China is seeking to replace the United
States as the dominant power in Asia. This conclusion represents a
typically indecent way of thinking -- gauge a noble heart with
one's own mean measure.
</P>
<P>
Comrade Deng Xiaoping said that socialist China should
demonstrate to the world with its practices that China is opposed
to hegemonism and power politics, that it will never seek hegemony
and that China is a steadfast force to maintain world peace.
</P>
<P>
He said, "China belongs to the third world. China will still be
a member of the third world and will never be a superpower even if
it becomes strong one day with its development."
</P>
<P>
The teachings of Deng Xiaoping were, are and will be the
guidelines of China's foreign policy.
</P>
<P>
China has always been pursuing a peaceful and independent
foreign policy. It holds that all countries, big or small, rich or
poor, strong or weak, are equal. China insists that developed
countries have the obligation to help with the development of
developing countries and that they do not have any right to bully
them.
</P>
<P>
The United States, styling itself as "world police", has a
habit of issuing orders to other countries and refuses to change
its course of action despite concerted condemnation and opposition
from other countries.
</P>
<P>
Now, fearing that a stronger China may become an obstacle to
its seeking hegemonism in Asia, the United States is acting like a
villain who sues his victim before he himself is prosecuted. Its
ultimate goal is to stifle China.
</P>
<P>
The absurd arguments fabricated by the authors, in essence, are
a revised version of the "China threat" theory created earlier by
the United States.
</P>
<P>
As an old Chinese saying goes, Cleverness may overreach
itself. The two authors of the book thought they could mislead the
world with a deceptive pamphlet and a few naive tricks.
</P>
<P>
But lies are lies.
</P>
<P>
One of their ancestors, Thomas Jefferson, has rightly said: You
can fool all the people some of the time and some of the people
all of the time, but you cannot fool all the people all of the
time. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
