<HEADLINE> Egypt Denies Sending Forces to Zaire </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, March 12 (Xinhua) -- Egypt today denied reports that
Egypt has sent military forces to participate in an international
peace-keeping force in Zaire and insisted that Egypt limit its
actions to the humanitarian domain.
</P>
<P>
Egyptian contributions to all countries of the region,
including Zaire, are mainly humanitarian, the Egyptian MENA news
agency said, citing an Egyptian diplomatic source who spoke on
condition of anonymity.
</P>
<P>
The Egyptian delegation that visited the region in January
under Health Minister Ismail Sallam, had discussed means of
providing humanitarian assistance to African countries within the
context of international relief efforts initiated by Cairo along
with other countries, he said.
</P>
<P>
Egypt backs reaching a political settlement in Zaire within an
African context without foreign intervention, the diplomatic
source noted.
</P>
<P>
Rebels fighting against the government of Zairean President
Mobutu Sese Seko have captured an expanse of eastern Zaire,
driving Rwandan Hutu refugees before them and threaten the key
garrison city of Kisangani on the Zaire River.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. Security Council last Friday called on the rebels to
declare a ceasefire and accept a five-point U.N. peace plan, which
Kinshasa accepted only under pressure from rebel advances. The
Zairean rebels refused the plan, standing by their demand for
direct talks with Seko. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
