<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Major News Items in Leading French Newspapers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, March 12 (Xinhua) -- The following are major news items
in leading French newspapers today:
</P>
<P>
Liberation:
</P>
<P>
-- French Minister of Environment Corinne Lepage Tuesday
announced measures on restricting automobile movements on days of
serious air pollution in the region of Paris. Under such
restrictions, automobiles with even registration numbers can only
run on even dates while those with odd registration numbers will
be allowed to come out on odd dates.
</P>
<P>
-- During the Nazi occupation period, France produced large
quantities of zyklon B gas for Nazi Germany which used it in gas
chambers to kill Jews, said history professor Annie Lacroix-Riz of
the University of Toulouse, who studied archives in a Paris hotel
where orders of the former German military administration were
kept.
</P>
<P>
Le Figaro:
</P>
<P>
-- French Prime Minister Alain Juppe Tuesday proposed to the
National Assembly a proportional system for women to run for the
legislature in the future. He suggested that a parity between men
and women be established as a tentative method for future
legislative elections for a period of 10 years.
</P>
<P>
-- The French government will announce the buyer of the state
defense electronics group Thomson-CSF before June 30. But it has
ruled out the participation by the state airspace group
Aerospatiale in taking over Thomson-CSF, in order to maintain
neutrality in the affair. The Alcatel-Alsthom group and the
Lagardere group are now bidding for the take-over of Thomson-CSF.
</P>
</TEXT>
