<HEADLINE> Russia to Pardon Law-Breaking Fighters in Chechnya </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, March 12 (Xinhua) -- The Russian State Duma (lower
house) today adopted a resolution granting amnesty to combatants
who broke laws in Chechnya.
</P>
<P>
The resolution, passed by 262 votes in favor, eight against and
six abstentions, will come into effect without the approval of the
Federation Council (upper house) and Russian President Boris
Yeltsin.
</P>
<P>
It is designed to ensure a peaceful settlement of the conflict
in the republic and will be implemented within six months over its
enactment.
</P>
<P>
The amnesty will cover those who committed socially dangerous
offenses in Chechnya, Daghestan, North Ossetia and the Stavropol
in the period between December 9, 1994 and December 31, 1996.
</P>
<P>
However, the amnesty will not cover servicemen and officers of
the Interior Ministry who stole firearms, ammunition, explosives
and sold them to illegal armed factions and persons who
participated in the conflict.
</P>
<P>
People who embezzled funds allocated for restoring economy in
Chechnya will not be pardoned. 
</P>
</TEXT>
