<HEADLINE> Hoesch-Krupp Profits Plunge 60 Percent Due to Steel Losses </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, March 12 (Xinhua) -- Germany's heavy industry group
Hoesch-Krupp said today that its profits in 1996 declined by some
60 percent to 208 million marks (121 million U.S. dollars) due to
losses in its steel operations.
</P>
<P>
The group said all other divisions made money last year except
the steel unit, which lost 56 million marks (about 37 million
dollars). It expected the steel operations to improve and the
overall profits to rise in 1997.
</P>
<P>
Hoesch-Krupp said its turnover in 1996 totaled 24 billion marks
(15.8 billion dollars), 500 million marks (330 million dollars)
more than that of 1995, which saw a record profit of 505 million
marks (333.3 million dollars).
</P>
<P>
Despite the profits downturn, Hoesch-Krupp said it would
continue from last year the payment of 5-mark dividend per 50-mark
share. 
</P>
