<HEADLINE> Microsoft to Turn Out New Internet Browser </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, March 12 (Xinhua) -- Microsoft, the world leading
software publisher, announced that it will soon release its
Internet Explorer 4.0 which is believed to make it easier to
integrate the Internet and the personal computer's desktop.
</P>
<P>
Preview versions of the highly anticipated browser will go to
developers this month. It will be ready for the public this
summer, according to a report of the USA Today.
</P>
<P>
Explorer 4.0 is significant because it puts most Windows 95
functions, including the "start" button -- which launches programs
-- right on the Internet browser.
</P>
<P>
The browser becomes the first screen a personal computer user
sees.
</P>
<P>
Microsoft said it is also trying to create an open standard for
so-called push technology and has signed partnerships to integrate
the technology into the Explorer 4.0 browser. The push services
automatically deliver information from a corporate network or the
Internet to an individual's PC. By using the technology, Explorer
can make that information as easy to get as a document sitting
inside the PC's hard drive.
</P>
<P>
The paper said that Netscape Communications, the leader in
browsers, is heading in the same direction. Its next-generation
browsers also are designed to be the main screen on a PC.
</P>
<P>
That boosts the already intense competition between Netscape
and Microsoft in the battle over how people will use PCs to
access information. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
