<HEADLINE> Ethio-Djibouti Railway Co. Incurs Loss </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, March 12 (Xinhua) -- The Ethio-Djibouti Railway
Company is incurring a monthly loss of 20,000 Birr (nearly 3,000
US Dollars), a report from the Ethiopian News Agency said today.
</P>
<P>
The report quoted Buh Hussein, general manager of the company
as saying that the company's monthly expenditure on Addis
Ababa-Djibouti route amounts to 150,000 Birr while its income is
only 130,000 Birr.
</P>
<P>
Hussein told workers at Dire Dawa, second largest city in
Ethiopia, that the maintenance of the locomotives and
tracks, expenditure on spare parts and fuel were the major factors
for the loss.
</P>
<P>
Unnecessary expenditures including maintenance of residential
quarters have raised the running cost, said the general manager.
</P>
<P>
However, the workers of the company were quoted by the report
as complaining that lack of control on the part of administrative
bodies, corruption, unplanned activities and shortage of
spare parts are the basic reasons for the loss.
</P>
<P>
The 781-km railway was built at the beginning of this century.
The company incurred loss in its operations in recent years due
to ageing locomotives and tracks as well as shortage of
spare-parts. A study enabling the company to become profitable has
been presented to the company's board for approval by the
governments of Ethiopia and Djibouti. 
</P>
</TEXT>
