<DOCNO> XIE19970313.0022 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Canada Relaxes Rules on High-Tech Immigrants </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, March 12 (Xinhua) -- The Canadian government has
decided to drastically shorten the processing time for high-tech
immigrants in a new bid to fill its vacant software jobs at home.
</P>
<P>
A new six-month pilot project, beginning from next month, will
reduce the time from several months to several weeks for those
with a firm job offer in one of six specific high-technology
categories, said reports today.
</P>
<P>
The project is said to be the result of months of lobbying by
the high technology industry for immigration rule changes.
</P>
<P>
The industry has blamed the shortage of qualified Canadians to
fill key jobs for slowing the development of many new products.
</P>
<P>
It is estimated that Canada now has about 15,000 vacant jobs in
six high-tech categories, including communications, multimedia,
management information, consulting, product development and
"imbedded" software.
</P>
<P>
Raphael Girard, assistant deputy minister for immigration, said
the experiment will end a time-consuming process that now forces
companies to prove there are no Canadians qualified to fill key
jobs.
</P>
<P>
Qualified immigrants with firm job offers will be issued
temporary work permits to enter Canada during the project, Girard
said.
</P>
<P>
The project has been welcomed by the industry, which is
expected to bring in 2,000 to 3,000 skilled specialists on
temporary immigration visas.
</P>
<P>
Yet, it also got its share of criticism from others, who
claimed that the government is rewarding companies that have
failed to develop skilled staff and helping immigrants to take
Canadian jobs. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970313.0023 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Germany Considers Delaying Euro Launching </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, March 12 (Xinhua) -- The German government is considering
to delay the planned 1999 launching of the European single
currency Euro, said local press reports today.
</P>
<P>
"The introduction of the Eruo may cause an economic catastrophe
in this country... Plans to delay the Eruo launching deadline are
circulating in Bonn," German news agency DPA quoted a report from
the news weekly Stern as saying.
</P>
<P>
Without citing sources, the latest edition of Stern to be
published Thursday, says that government officials are considering
to delay the start-up of the Eruo and the setting of currency
exchange rates for one or two years.
</P>
<P>
European Union (EU) countries are required to comply with
strict limits on budget deficits and public debts this year before
being allowed to launch the Eruo. Stern says that among the 15 EU
members, only Luxembourg and Finland appear set to meet the
criteria easily in 1997.
</P>
<P>
Germany has failed to meet the criteria in recent years, and is
expected to fail again this year with a record post-1930s
unemployment and a sluggish economic upswing.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, German Finance Minister Theo Waigel has reiterated
that there would be no watering down of the admission criteria.
</P>
<P>
A decision on delaying the Eruo launching will be made at the
EU summit scheduled for June or sometime later this autumn in
Amsterdam, says Stern. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970313.0024 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Boeing Sees Jet Demand Rising Over Next 20 Years </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, March 12 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. Boeing Co. projected
that the worldwide demand for new airplanes will increase quickly
despite anticipated lower air traffic growth, the Journal of
Commerce reported today.
</P>
<P>
Boeing expected in its current market outlook report that the
demand of new passenger and cargo planes the world over will
exceed 16,100 in the next 20 years, worthing more than 1.1
trillion U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
The outlook forecast an annual worldwide air travel growth of
4.9 percent from 1997 to 2016, down slightly from last year's
prediction of 5.1 percent.
</P>
<P>
In 2016, the world fleet will total 23,600 passenger and cargo
planes, it said.
</P>
<P>
Asia-Pacific markets will continue to be the hot spot for
traffic and equipment growth. The region will lead with 33 percent
of the world demand for new planes over the next 20 years, down
slightly from the 1996 forecast of 35 percent.
</P>
<P>
Boeing Co., the world's largest airplane maker, is seeking a
world market share of 67 percent. Boeing officials said that it
"will fight every battle and will not back off on any campaign"
in the competition with other airplane makers. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
