<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zimbabwe, World Bank Reach Accord </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, March 12 (Xinhua) -- Zimbabwe and the World Bank today
reached agreement on a 100 million U.S. Dollars development
assistant program aimed at supporting the country's objective of
poverty reduction and promoting economic growth.
</P>
<P>
The pact was reached at the end of two-day intensive
consultations between the bank and the Zimbabwe government on
development cooperation projects to be implemented in 1997 and
beyond.
</P>
<P>
The bank said during the discussions, the Zimbabwe government
had strongly reaffirmed its commitment to the economic reform
program and indicated that a variety of initiatives were being
implemented to further deregulate the economy and reform the
public sector.
</P>
<P>
In particular, it said in a statement issued at the end of the
talks, Harare indicated that actions were being taken to reduce
the public sector's deficit by redefining the role of the
government and rationalizing the civil service.
</P>
<P>
Besides, other steps include overhauling the planning,
budgeting and expenditure control system, strengthening tax
administration, and accelerating the privatization and
commercialization of public enterprises.
</P>
<P>
The bank expressed strong support for the Zimbabwe
government's reform program and indicated that timely
implementation of these actions was necessary to further improve
the investment climate and to guarantee much-needed employment.
</P>
<P>
The bank said its assistance strategy to Zimbabwe would
include helping the government with the design of macro-economic
reforms to stimulate growth, reduce inflation and place greater
emphasis on rural development, natural resource management and
the environment. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
