<HEADLINE> Greece Welcomes Appointment of New Albanian PM </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ATHENS, March 12 (Xinhua) -- Greece today welcomed the
appointment of a new Albanian prime minister, saying developments
on the political front gave rise to "guarded optimism" for a
resolution of the crisis.
</P>
<P>
"We hope that following the appointment of a prime minister the
attempts to form a national unity government will bear fruit,"
government spokesman Dimitris Reppas said.
</P>
<P>
Albanian President Sali Berisha appointed Bashkim Fino, an
economist from the opposition Socialist party, new prime minister
Tuesday in a bid to halt an armed rebellion sweeping the south.
</P>
<P>
Reppas said that there was a possibility of a representative of
the Greek government -- most probably Foreign Undersecretary
Yiannos Kranidiotis -- visiting Albania soon and that his contacts
would include meetings with representatives of the rebels since
"armed rebels played a role and could not be ignored in political
developments."
</P>
<P>
Kranidiotis visited Tirana last Saturday to meet with Albanian
President Berisha and members of opposition parties.
</P>
<P>
Responding to charges that the Athens government was
"supporting" Berisha, Reppas said, "The government is bolstering
ties with Albania to the benefit of the Greek monority as well as
security and stability in the region."
</P>
<P>
Greece shares a common border of some 150 kilometers with
Albania and there are about 300,000 ethnic Greeks living in the
neighboring country, mainly in southern Albania. 
</P>
</TEXT>
