</P>
<P>
The New York Times:
</P>
<P>
-- Jordan's King Hussein wrote Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin
Netanyahu a personal and forceful letter saying that he could not
continue as the Israel's partner and friend. The King accused
Netanyahu of taking decisions amounting to continued deliberate
humiliation of the Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
-- The World Bank and the International Monetary Fund will soon
forgive some loans made to about 20 of the poorest nations,
beginning with Uganda, in an effort to reduce the debt burden
plaguing them. The agencies said they expected to slash as much as
300 million U.S. dollars from Uganda's international debts of 3.4
billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
The Washington Post:
</P>
<P>
-- When the Clinton administration released a long-awaited
report to Congress last month on the costs of NATO enlargement, it
appeared to offer the best of all worlds: a low-budget extension
into East Europe that would gratify tight-fisted legislators, ease
defense burdens for prospective new members and defuse an ominous
showdown with Russia. But defense analysts in Europe and the
United States say the "enlargement on the cheap" strategy may be
too optimistic even in the absence of any visible threat to the
alliance.
</P>
<P>
-- Russian President Boris Yeltsin ordered a sweeping shake-up
of his government Tuesday, pledging to slash the bloated Russian
bureaucracy and warning that every senior official's job is on the
line except for those of his top two lieutenants.
</P>
<P>
The Wall Street Journal:
</P>
<P>
-- Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat invited U.S., European and
Arab envoys to a Gaza conference this weekend to discuss Middle
East peace in light of Israel's decision to build housing in East
Jerusalem. The United States, over Israeli objections, will
attend. Meanwhile, Jordan's King Hussein wrote Netanyahu saying he
has lost confidence in Israel's prime minister as a peace
partner.  
</P>
