<HEADLINE> Russia, NATO Near Agreement on New Partnership: </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, March 12 (Xinhua) -- Russia and the North Atlantic
Treaty Organization (NATO) have achieved enough progress towards a
new partnership, said a local news report today.
</P>
<P>
The Washington Post said that an agreement between Moscow and
the alliance could be ready for signing by President Boris Yeltsin
and the alliance's 16 heads of state at a special summit in May or
June.
</P>
<P>
"In a key concession, Russia now seems ready to drop its
insistence on a legally binding treaty that would have to be
ratified by all parliaments and has signaled a willingness to
accept NATO's preference for a political document endorsed by
government leaders," the report said.
</P>
<P>
It quoted senior NATO officials as saying that the new
flexibility was evident in the latest discussions on a NATO-Russia
pact, which was held Sunday in Moscow by Russian Foreign Minister
Yevgeny Primakov and NATO Secretary General Javier Solana.
</P>
<P>
"Primakov may elaborate further on Moscow's new thinking when
he visits Washington later this week to plan the U.S.-Russia
summit scheduled for Helsinki on March 20," the paper added.
</P>
<P>
However, Russia has not muted its opposition toward NATO's
eastward expansion, the report quoted Western officials as saying.
</P>
<P>
NATO has said that it will decide to invite central and eastern
European countries to join the alliance at a summit meeting in
Madrid in July. Russia strongly opposes the move. 
</P>
</TEXT>
