<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> German Minister Rules Out Higher Coal Mining Subsidies </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, March 12 (Xinhua) -- German Economic Minister Guenter
Rexrodt said today he saw no possibility for the government to
raise subsidies for the unprofitable coal mining industry, though
the protesting coal miners' blockade of the government district
here entered its third day.
</P>
<P>
In an interview with Berlin's B.Z. daily, Rexrodt described as
"generous" the 4 billion marks (about 2.4 billion U.S. dollars) of
annual subsidies to be offered by Bonn to the bituminous coal
mines in the west of Germany from year 2005.
</P>
<P>
This was the best the government could do given its financial
situation, Rexrodt added.
</P>
<P>
Some 3,500 miners today continued blocking Bonn's main
north-south artery and maintained a barricade around the
headquarters of Rexrodt's Free Democratic Party, the junior
partner in Chancellor Helmut Kohl's center-right government.
</P>
<P>
A total of 10,000 miners were expected to join a rally later
today in Bonn, to continue protest against the government's plans
to slash annual federal subsidies for coal mining from the 10
billion marks (about 5.8 billion dollars) currently to 5.5 billion
marks (about 3.2 billion dollars) as from year 2005.
</P>
<P>
Of the continuing subsidies, Bonn will pay up to 4 billion
marks (about 2.35 billion dollars), with the rest paid by North
Rhine-Westphalia state.
</P>
<P>
Miners' trade union IG Bergbau has warned of mass unemployment
in the coal mining regions of the Ruhr Valley and Saarland as a
result of the quick pace of subsidy cuts. In February, Germany's
unemployment reached a post-1930s record high of 4.67 million, or
12.2 percent.
</P>
<P>
Against the blockade of some 15,000 miners several hundred
yards off his chancellery, Kohl Tuesday postponed the due talks
with IG Bergbau leader Hans Berger on subsidy cuts to Thursday,
saying he would not let himself be put under pressure.
</P>
<P>
Berger Tuesday asked the miners to call off protests and await
the results of Thursday's talks, but the proposal was apparently
defied by protesters.
</P>
<P>
The trade union is demanding 6.5 billion marks (about 3.82
billion dollars) in annual subsidies from 2005 and say miners are
willing to reduce the coal mining workforce to 45,000.
</P>
<P>
Under the government plan, only about 30,000 jobs of a total of
85,000 in western German mines would remain by 2005.
</P>
<P>
In 1996, the loss-making deep-pit coal mines in the west of
Germany received a record state handout of 11.2 billion marks
(about 6.59 billion dollars), with 10 billion (about 5.88 dollars)
from Bonn and the rest from North Rhine-Westphalia.
</P>
<P>
German bituminous coal costs 280 marks (about 165 dollars) per
ton, compared with 80 marks (about 47 dollars) per ton for the
same kind of coal purchased on international markets. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
