<BODY>
<HEADLINE> DESY Discovery Possible Clue for "New Physics" </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, March 12 (Xinhua) -- Physicists at the German Elektron
Synchrotron (DESY) in Hamburg have found evidence that could
result in "new physics", with further data to be taken this year
for confirmation.
</P>
<P>
According to German news agency DPA reports today, DESY
scientists have in experiments registered data that cannot be
explained by today's theories.
</P>
<P>
They find a positron that can collide with a proton in such a
manner that it is deflected at a wide angle, thus gaining enormous
momentum. By February 19, scientists there had registered 11 such
events -- far more than expected on the basis of theoretical
predictions.
</P>
<P>
The experiments were conducted with HERA, the Hadron Electron
Accumulation Ring, Germany's largest and most expensive scientific
apparatus.
</P>
<P>
HERA is a ring-shaped particle accelerator with a circumference
of 6.3 kilometers which runs in an underground tunnel. It
accelerates both protons and positrons to almost the speed of
light, and the particles collide head-on in the tunnel beam.
</P>
<P>
DESY physicists believe that if the initial evidence were
confirmed, the so-called standard model of physics to date should
be radically shaken.
</P>
<P>
According to the DPA reports, more will be known in October
when the next data-taking period are completed.
</P>
<P>
Possible theoretical explanations of what is happening at DESY
include super symmetry -- extension of the standard model which is
purely hypothetical as yet, with the support from many experts.
</P>
<P>
Another possible cause of the high number of registered events may
be so-called leptoquark -- an exotic elementary particle. A hitherto
unknown natural force could also be causing the new interaction.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970313.0042 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Greece to Make Banking Sector More Competitive </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ATHENS, March 12 (Xinhua) -- The Greek government is planning
sweeping changes to make the Greek banking sector more effective
and competitive on an international level, National Economy and
Finance Minister Yiannos Papantoniou said today.
</P>
<P>
"The basic government philosophy in the banking sector is the
creation of relatively large banking units with diversified
activities as well as increased stakes in the share capital of
state-run banks," Papantoniou told bankers at a meeting of the
General Assembly of the Association of Greek Banks.
</P>
<P>
He said the first concrete indications of this philosophy would
be seen in the next few months with the immediate re-tendering of
Cretabank, the continuation of reforms of the Agricultural Bank of
Greece into a modern commercial bank and the sale of the Bank of
Central Greece.
</P>
<P>
Moves to merge the Ionian and commercial banks and the national
housing and mortgage banks would be well under way by the end of
the year, he added.
</P>
<P>
Governor of the Bank of Greece Lucas Papademos said all current
restrictions on foreign exchange accounts in Greek banks would be
lifted soon.
</P>
<P>
Papademos told the meeting that commercial banks needed to
modernize to become more competitive and effective.
</P>
<P>
The main prerequisites for growth in the banking sector, he
said, were the reduction of operation costs, the expansion of
portfolios and the reduction of risks. 
</P>
</TEXT>
