<HEADLINE> Kissinger Urges U.S. to Keep Cooperative Ties With China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, March 12 (Xinhua) -- Former U.S. secretary of state
Henry Kissinger said here today that the U.S. government should
keep a "cooperative and realistic relationship" with China and
avoid conflict between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
Kissinger made the remarks in a speech at a forum of Philippine
businessmen, legislators and diplomats.
</P>
<P>
"I believe we should do our best to have a cooperative but
realistic relationship with China, willing to give them a real
stake in international system and welcoming their participation,"
he said.
</P>
<P>
He also warned that the U.S. will face resistance from China if
the U.S. government trys to tell China what it should do.
</P>
<P>
"The U.S. history is two hundred years, China history five
thousand. In Chinese history they have been putting dynasties,
every one of them have last long or longer than entire history of
the US," Kissenger said.
</P>
<P>
"So therefore the U.S. attempt to lecture China on its domestic
situation, there is certain resistance because the Chinese believe
they have managed for 4800 years without significant advice from
the U.S.," he said.
</P>
<P>
Kissenger said China has experienced great changes in the past
decades, the growth of China is a basic fact and the international
system must get used to that reality.
</P>
<P>
Kissinger, who had served as foreign policy adviser to three
former U.S. presidents, also castigated the current U.S. policy to
browbeat trading partners on human rights.
</P>
<P>
He said it is "absurd" for the U.S. government to believe that
"two hundred and fifty million Americans can tell all the billions
of the people in the rest of the world what form of government
they must have and by what kind of domestic practices."  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
