<HEADLINE> EU Must Be Made for Its Own People: Santer </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, March 12 (Xinhua) -- The European Union (EU) must
change its ways and focus more clearly on the aspirations of its
people if it wants their support, European Commission President
Jacques Santer said today.
</P>
<P>
Addressing the European Parliament EU assembly in Strasbourg,
France, during a ceremony to mark the 40th anniversary of the
Treaty of Rome, Santer said that in its haste to create a single
market, the EU had left other, vital concerns by the wayside,
"with dramatic implications at times."
</P>
<P>
"Our joint project... has to be to reflect the feelings and
aspirations of our citizens," he told the assembly.
</P>
<P>
People would not back the union if it did not also tackle
unemployment and give them proper social and health protection, he
added. He was speaking a day after thousands of European car
workers protested in Paris against plans by carmaker Renault to
close an assembly plant in Belgium, with the loss of 3,000 jobs.
</P>
<P>
The EU had succeeded in abolishing national borders for
criminals but not for national police forces, Santer said, adding
that it had a common trade policy but hadn't been able to reap
political benefits from it.
</P>
<P>
The EC president said EU governments needed to tackle all these
problems during their ongoing reform of the EU treaty. 
</P>
