<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-12 18:34 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> International Conference Aiming at Rescuing Peace </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, March 12 (Xinhua) -- Palestinian leader Yasser
Arafat said today the upcoming international conference in Gaza
was designed to rescue the Israeli-Palestinian peace process
from the current crisis.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to about 100 visiting Israeli businessmen, Arafat
said that the Palestinian National Authority (PNA) was still
committed to peace despite of the current crisis created by
Israel's violations of peace accords.
</P>
<P>
He said the conference of foreign diplomats, due to be held
Saturday in Gaza, would discuss the Israeli violations and their
impact on the Israeli-Palestinian peace talks.
</P>
<P>
Arafat's spokesman Abu Rudeineh today called on the
international community to put pressure on Israel to "implement
accurately and honestly" the peace accords signed by both sides.
</P>
<P>
He denied Israel's accusation that the conference was a
violation of the Oslo agreement. "No, it's a part of the
agreement which says that whenever there is a problem, there
must be supervision. This supervision is by those who signed the
agreement," he said, referring to the United States, Russia and
Norway which sponsored the Oslo accord.
</P>
<P>
The PNA has issued invitations to the U.S., Russia, Norway,
Japan, the European Union and Arab countries to attend the
conference. Rudeineh said all these invited had accepted the
invitation.
</P>
<P>
Despite Israel's strong opposition, the U.S. government has
decided to accept the invitation by sending its Consul-General
in Jerusalem Edward Abington to take part in the meeting.
</P>
<P>
U.S. Ambassador Martin Indyk rejected the claim that the
U.S.-Israeli relations were in crisis due to the U.S. agreement
to attend the meeting. He said the U.S. agreed to attend only
because it wanted to conduct the dialogue with the Palestinian
side in order to continue the peace process.
</P>
<P>
Israel today continued condemning the holding of the
international conference as a violation of the peace
agreement. Foreign Minister David Levy warned that such a meeting
would only put the peace process into deep freeze.
</P>
<P>
Israeli Prime Minister Binyamin Netanyahu, currently visiting
Russia, said in Moscow that the Gaza conference was against
Israel and violating the peace agreement. He also accused the PNA
of violating the peace agreements by failing to change the
Palestinian Charter calling for Israel's destruction, refusing
to collect illegal weapons and having released anti-Israeli
Islamic terrorists.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu urged Arafat to stop threatening with violence
whenever there was a crisis and come back to the negotiating
table. He said the PNA would make a mistake if it broke off
contacts with Israel. Local media reports said that Arafat had
refused to receive telephone calls from Netanyahu in recent days
to protest Israel's recent actions.
</P>
<P>
The current crisis was caused by Israel's unilateral decision
on the scope of further troop pullbacks on the West Bank, its
plan to build the Har Homa settlement in East Jerusalem and its
order to close four PNA offices in East Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
Arafat is to convene Thursday a meeting of the Palestinian
Council in Bethlehem and another meeting of the Central
Committee of the Palestinian Liberation Organization Friday in
order to formulate further response to Israel's tough stance.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970313.0049 </DOCNO>
