<HEADLINE> Russia, Uzbekistan Sign Economic Cooperation Accords </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, March 12 (Xinhua) -- Russian Prime Minister Viktor
Chernomyrdin and his Uzbek counterpart Utkir Sultanov today signed
a package of agreements and protocols on Russia-Uzbekistan
economic cooperation in 1998-2000.
</P>
<P>
According to Itar-Tass news agency, the Russian prime minister
said that the cooperation agreements cover all fields including
agriculture, chemistry, petrochemical and non-ferrous industries.
</P>
<P>
Chernomyrdin said: "We also have agreed at the meeting on the
formation of large financial-industrial groups."
</P>
<P>
He expressed hope that the agreements would promote the
bilateral economic cooperation.
</P>
<P>
The two sides also signed an agreement on joint production of
Ilyushin-114 aircraft for local airlines.
</P>
<P>
The aircraft is planned to be manufactured in Uzbekistan and
equipped with Russian engines and avionics.
</P>
<P>
The two countries also agreed to cooperate in combating drug
smuggling.
</P>
<P>
Uzbek Prime Minister Sultanov stressed the need for a strategy
which would expand trade relations between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
Chernomyrdin admitted that the bilateral trade decreased in the
recent years.
</P>
<P>
Sultanov arrived in Moscow on Monday for an official visit to
Russia. 
