<HEADLINE> S. African Regional Cereal Sufficient for This </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, March 12 (Xinhua) -- Regional cereal availability at
28.12 million tons will be sufficient to cover consumption and
strategic reserve requirements for the southern African region.
</P>
<P>
This was disclosed by the 12-member Southern African
Development Community (SADC) food security unit today referring
to revised food security assessments for the region's current
marketing year.
</P>
<P>
In a report released in Harare, the unit said that regional
consumption and strategic requirements demand only 26.79 million
tons, leaving a surplus of 1.33 million tons.
</P>
<P>
''Most SADC countries expect cereal harvests which are either
equal to or higher than last season, should favorable rainfall
conditions prevail until the end of the season,'' said the
report.
</P>
<P>
In Zimbabwe, the unit said, maize production is expected to
surpass last year's above average harvest of 2.6 million tons, or
at the very least, remain at the same level.
</P>
<P>
The unit said Malawi, Zambia, Swaziland and Namibia are the
other countries expecting increased maize production.
</P>
<P>
It added despite heavy rains, potential crop yields are
unlikely to be achieved in Angola and Mozambique. And production
in Botswana is likely to remain low. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
