<HEADLINE> Killings, Violence Occur in Johannesburg </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, March 12 (Xinhua) -- At least two people were
killed and many others wounded today in shootings linked to a
demonstration by thousands of Zulu people marking the 1994 Shell
House massacre, police and medical workers said.
</P>
<P>
The wild shooting, which broke out at Johannesburg's Library
Gardens at 2:15 p.m., was sparked by one or two shots, apparently
fired from the crowd, followed by a 30-second volley of automatic
fire, South African Press Association quoted unidentified
witnesses as saying.
</P>
<P>
It was not yet clear who was responsible for the shooting.
</P>
<P>
The so-called Shell House massacre refers to the shooting n
March 28, 1994 when eight Zulu protesters were shot dead,
allegedly by security guards of African National Congress (ANC)
outside the party's Johannesburg headquarters.
</P>
<P>
At least another 50 people were killed and over 170 injured in
clashes between Zulu nationalists, policemen and ANC supporters
in and around Johannesburg on that day.
</P>
<P>
Mourners decided to stage the march and service today because
March 28 falls on Good Friday this year.
</P>
<P>
Earlier in the day, about 20,000 Zulu people, almost all of
them armed with sticks, held demonstrations in downtown streets
in Johannesburg under the watchful eye of almost 2,000 police and
troops in armored vehicles, supported by a police helicopter.
</P>
<P>
The demonstrators called on South African President Nelson
Mandela to appear in court to answer charges in connection with
the 1994 Shell House massacre 
</P>
</TEXT>
