<HEADLINE> Arab Businessmen Oppose Regional Cooperation With </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, March 12 (Xinhua) -- Arab businessmen today agreed to
work toward a common Arab market but opposed the establishment of
a regional businessmen council that will involve Israel in the
region's economic integration process.
</P>
<P>
"It is premature to form such a council as the peace process
has not yet been completed on the Palestinian, Syrian and Lebanese
tracks," Arab Businessmen Council (ABC) Chairman Hamdi al-Tabba
said at a press conference held at the end of the two-day meetings
of the Arab Businessmen Council.
</P>
<P>
The council cannot be established with Israel's participation
as long as Israel still "monopolizes the Palestinian market and
rejects opening it to Arab products," he said.
</P>
<P>
The chairman said the council endeavors to facilitate the
transfer of Palestinian products to Arab markets and the movement
of Palestinian businessmen in the Arab world,
</P>
<P>
He denied any differences over the council's performance among
the Arab states and welcomed any Arab country to join the council.
</P>
<P>
Wrapping up the meetings here today, Arab businessmen agreed
to work towards the establishment of the Arab Free Trade Zone in
January 1998 in conformity with the decision taken by the Arab
ministers of economy here last month.
</P>
<P>
They also reached an agreement on establishing a data network
for Arab businessmen to get acquainted with investment
opportunities in the Arab world and exchange information on
ventures, the chairman said.
</P>
<P>
The meetings covered means of enhancing economic, trade and
investment cooperation among the Arab countries, he added.
</P>
<P>
The ABC also held a lengthy meeting today with Arab League
Secretary General Esmat Abdul-Meguid during which they discussed
the role of the private sector in economic and social development
in the Arab countries and cooperation between the Arab League and
Arab businessmen.
</P>
<P>
It also dealt with the need to take steps towards facilitating
the movement of Arab businessmen and Arab goods in the Arab
world. 
</P>
</TEXT>
