<HEADLINE> Ethiopia Uses Pulse Seeds As Natural Fertilizers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, March 12 (Xinhua) -- About 300 pulse seeds
believed to sustain soil fertility and serve as natural
fertilizers have been gathered in Ethiopia, a biological expert
from the Ministry of Agriculture said today.
</P>
<P>
Asfaw Haile-Mariam told local journalists that seeds selected
from these pulses through laboratory tests, in house experiments
and demonstration centers will be distributed to multipliers
during the next crop season in Ethiopia.
</P>
<P>
Asfaw said peasants in different parts have long experiences
in using biological fertilizers.
</P>
<P>
He said countries such as China, India and Indonesia take a
prominent place in using these biological fertilizers produced
cheaply and helping to prevent air pollution.
</P>
<P>
The national soil research laboratory of Ethiopia has a plan
to conduct in-depth studies about biological fertilizers in
cooperation with the national fertilizer agency, he added.
</P>
