<HEADLINE> Athens Suitable for 2004 Olympic Games: Report </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ATHENS, March 12 (Xinhua) -- The Athens of 2004 will be an
idyll of parklands and will have no traffic problems or air
pollution, said a report on the repercussions of major public
works projects.
</P>
<P>
The report, released today, was prepared by Greek and foreign
scientists. It said that the public works projects currently under
way will significantly improve the quality of life in the Greek
capital, in time for the 2004 Olympic Games which Athens hopes to
host.
</P>
<P>
The report was commissioned by the Athens 2004 Olympics
Committee, which has also drafted an action plan, in cooperation
with the country's Environment, Town Planning and Public Works
Ministry, to upgrade the quality of life and to protect the
environment, given that environmental factors play a role in the
selection of cities to host the games.
</P>
<P>
The International Olympic Committee recently put Athens
alongside Rome as front-runners for the 2004 games but stressed
that Athens suffocating air pollution was the greatest obstacle to
the Greek capital's bid.
</P>
<P>
But the scientific report noted that since 1990 smog levels in
the city have shown a gradual reduction and that the completion of
the metro subway system, the international airport at Spata, the
construction of a number of major road axes and the introduction
of use of natural gas in industry would all contribute
significantly to further reduction of air and noise pollution.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the supervisor of the Athens 2004 action plan,
Kostas Liaskas, said the program will relate to planning and
construction of sports facilities, land use, transport, energy,
environmental management and other factors.
</P>
<P>
"In the year 2004, the Olympic Games will be held in a clean,
healthy and attractive Athens, which will be in the future a pole
of attraction for tourists and services, but will also meet the
desires of residents and the needs of production," he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
