<HEADLINE> China: Developed Countries Cling to Confrontation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, March 12 (Xinhua) -- Chinese Alternate Representative
Li Baodong said here today that representatives from developed
countries had turned a deaf ear to sincere appeals for cooperation
put forward by those from developing countries.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the 53rd session of the United Nations Commission
on Human Rights, Li said that the speech made this afternoon by
Dutch Deputy Prime Minister and Minister for Foreign Affairs Hans
Van Mierlo "is such an example."
</P>
<P>
Li said that Van Mierlo unfoundedly accused China of violating
human rights in his speech on behalf of the European Union (EU).
However, Li stressed, Van Mierlo "probably has forgotten two
things."
</P>
<P>
"First, the human rights record in the history of the
Netherlands is by no means glorious. During their colonization
process and colonial rule over several centuries, the Dutch
colonialists violated human rights on a massive and systematic
scale, the consequences of which have not been eliminated
completely even till today," said Li.
</P>
<P>
He said, "Secondly, he has forgotten to look at his own
backyard in Western Europe. At the end of last year, a notorious
case of pedophilia was exposed in a member state of the European
Union, which shocked the people in that country as well as the
whole world. However, Van Mierlo did not even say a word about
this case."
</P>
<P>
Intolerably, Li said, "while addressing the commission, he took
himself for a teacher and the delegates of developing countries
for pupils with ears only for his harangue."
</P>
<P>
Li noted, "The first and foremost principle of the UN Charter
is sovereign equality. He is in no position to admonish us. I
would like to suggest that he had better concentrate on reviewing
the ignoble human rights record in the history of his own country
and on tackling the human rights problems within the EU."
</P>
<P>
At a press conference given after his speech at the session,
Van Mierblelo insisted that the EU is prepared to table a draft
resolution against China, but the final decision has not yet been
made.
</P>
<P>
The current session of the UN Commission on Human Rights meets
here in Geneva from March 10 to April 18. 
</P>
</TEXT>
