<HEADLINE> UK Children Shun Beef on BSE Worries </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, March 12 (Xinhua) -- Of Britain's 4-11-year-old
children, 38 percent have given up eating beef and 20 percent is
shunning most meat because of worries over BSE, or mad cow
disease, according to a report today by the Vegetarian Society
(VS).
</P>
<P>
The report, which was based on a sample of nearly 1,000 parents
and a total of almost 1,500 children, was conducted as there are
widespread concerns in the country that BSE can be passed from
infected cattle to the human race.
</P>
<P>
Stephen Connor, communications manager of the VS, said that
almost a quarter of the children in the age group were avoiding
meat, which showed that they would be comfortable with a
vegetarian diet in the future.
</P>
<P>
On average, 7 percent of British adults are vegetarians at
present. However, the report said that the figure would increase
in the future.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the report said most parents believed that a
vegetarian child could be as healthy as a meat-eating child.
</P>
</TEXT>
