<HEADLINE> NATO Expansion Could Cost Britain 2 Billion Pounds </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, March 12 (Xinhua) -- The enlargement of the North
Atlantic Treaty Organization (NATO) could cost Britain more than
2 billion pounds (about 3.24 billion U.S. dollars) over the next
13 years.
</P>
<P>
The estimate of Britain's contribution to the NATO expansion is
based on the country's present share of the existing NATO budget,
according to a research report by the British-American Security
Information Council.
</P>
<P>
Military experts say that if Britain's share is as high as 3.24
billion dollars or 324 million dollars each year, it would be more
than the Pentagon's estimate of American costs, which would be
around 1.5 to 2 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
In a document published recently, the Pentagon estimated that
the total cost of NATO expansion would be between 27 and 35
billion dollars from 1997 to 2009 and a third of this would be
provided by the new NATO members themselves.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that the full costs to the alliance would be
revealed to NATO's North Atlantic Council in May, but NATO
officials believe that some of the costs would be met by savings
elsewhere, including pruning the 65 NATO headquarters to about 20.
</P>
</TEXT>
