<HEADLINE> British Envoy Makes Contacts on Cyprus Problem </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, March 12 (Xinhua) -- Britain's envoy on Cyprus,
Sir David Hannay said here today he hoped that direct
negotiations between the Greek and Turkish Cypriot sides on the
island will start within the first half of this year.
</P>
<P>
Sir David, who arrived here Tuesday for a new round of
contacts on the island, made the remark after a two-hour
meeting with President Glafcos Clerides, which he described as
"a very good talk".
</P>
<P>
He told reporters that he is working very closely with
the United Nations in a bid to find a solution to the protracted
Cyprus problem.
</P>
<P>
"There is an intensive preparatory process underway," he said,
noting this is led by the U.N. and "we are hopefully
strengthening and assisting this process."
</P>
<P>
Sir David said his talks and contacts in Cyprus are not
separate in any way. "It is all part of a concerted effort
by the international community led by the United Nations to
find the way through the problems that have previously blocked
the solution," he added.
</P>
<P>
He expressed the hope that the U.N. Chief will convene
face-to-face negotiations between two communities' leaders before
the end of the first half of 1997.
</P>
<P>
Sir David also discussed today the Cyprus problem with
Foreign Minister Alecos Michaelides in what he said "a very
useful, friendly and constructive way".
</P>
<P>
In the afternoon, he crossed into the Turkish-controlled
northern part of the island to meet with Turkish Cypriot
leader Rauf Denktash.
</P>
<P>
Sir David's visit follows a U.N.-sponsored proximity talks
between the Greek and Turkish Cypriot sides, which started
Monday.
</P>
<P>
U.N. Secretary-General's Resident Representative in Cyprus Gustave
Feissel described Tuesday his first contacts with President
Clerides and Denktash as "a good start".
</P>
<P>
The on-going proximity talks are aimed to pave the way
for the face-to-face negotiations between President Clerides and
Turkish Cypriot leader Denktash seeking solution to the Cyprus
problem.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has been divided since 1974 when Turkish troops
occupied 37 percent of the island in the wake of an
Athens-backed coup. 
</P>
