<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EC Adopts Strategy to Combat Acidification </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, March 12 (Xinhua) -- The European Commission has
stepped up its efforts to combat acidification by adopting today a
proposal on a strategy to reduce the levels of acid deposition in
the European Union (EU).
</P>
<P>
The strategy will, by 2010, reduce significantly the extent of
the areas in the EU where the tolerance of sensitive ecosystems to
acidity is exceeded.
</P>
<P>
According to the commission, main elements of the strategy
include establishment of national emission ceilings for each acid
rain pollutant, ratification of the UN protocol on further
reduction of sulphur emissions, and proposal for a directive
limiting the sulphur content of heavy fuel oils.
</P>
<P>
Other elements are revision of the EU's so-called Large
Combustion Plants Directive, promotion of cost-effective measures
to reduce emissions in countries in Central and Eastern Europe,
and designation of the Baltic Sea and the North Sea as so called
sulphur dioxide control areas.
</P>
<P>
The EC's current predictions indicate that the extent of
affected areas in 2010 would, in the absence of the strategy, be
8.7 million hectares. With the strategy this figure will be
reduced to 4.5 million hectares, the commission said.
</P>
<P>
According to EU figures, a total of 33.4 million tons of
sulphur dioxide, oxides of nitrogen and ammonia, three major
culprits for acidification, were emitted in the EU in 1990.
</P>
</TEXT>
