<HEADLINE> U.S. Trade Official Ends Visit to Saudi Arabia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, March 12 (Xinhua) -- Adviser to the U.S. Trade
Office Ian Kalisky wrapping up a tow-day visit to Saudi Arabia at
the head of a commercial delegation today called for opening the
Gulf doors for foreign investors.
</P>
<P>
He told a press conference before leaving the Kingdom that the
U.S. called on the Gulf Cooperation Council states to encourage
the private sector and the privatization to pave the way for
increased foreign investments, Kuwait News Agency reports from
Saudi capital city of Riyadh said.
</P>
<P>
He was also quoted as saying that Oman and Saudi Arabia could
join the World Trade Organization after they have reformed their
economic and trade structures.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. official arrived in Saudi Arabia Tuesday in response
to an invitation by Saudi Chambers of Commerce and Industry
Council for talks on more investments and opening new marketing
outlets for Saudi products in the U.S. markets.
</P>
<P>
Kalisky said during his stay in Riyadh, he discussed with
Saudi commercial officials means to bolster economic cooperations
between the two countries. Their talks also reviewed the outcome
of activities of joint teams that met in Washington last June and
the seventh round of talks between the two sides held in Bahrain
last year.
</P>
<P>
Deliberations also tackled double taxation, investment and
trade exchanges, he said.
</P>
<P>
Kalisky toured the Gulf earlier and conferred with Gulf
officials on means to promote economic, investment and trade
ties. In 1996, the Gulf-U.S. trade exchange was up to 25 billion
U.S. dollars or 14 percent over the year before.
</P>
<P>
Kalisky also claimed that the U.S. Mideast policy was
mainly to support peace and to ensure closer trade cooperation
with the Middle East countries including north Africa and
Israel. 
