<HEADLINE> Moi Pays High Tribute to Media's Role </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, March 12 (Xinhua) -- Kenyan President Daniel arap Moi
today said that "the role of the media in the social and economic
development of any nation must not be underestimated."
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the inauguration of a new printing plant here
today, the president stressed that media is "an agent to
influence thought and social changes".
</P>
<P>
He warned that the influence that the media has on the
thinking and conduct of people "must never be used to weaken the
positive aspects of the culture of our people or to undermine the
moral fabric of society".
</P>
<P>
Moi pointed out that a partisan press is a great danger to
democracy and good governance.
</P>
<P>
On the same occasion, the Aga Khan, who is on a visit to Kenya,
described the social obligation of the press as "resisting the
siren song of sensationalism and sectarianism (which is used) as
ways to build short-term readership and short-term profits."
</P>
<P>
The new printing plant, which was built by the Nation Group of
Kenya set up by the Aga Khan in 1960, is one of the most advanced
facilities on the African continent today.
</P>
<P>
The Nation Group is the first newspaper company, outside of
the United States, to employ web-offset printing and computerized
type-setting, according to a press release issued here today.
</P>
<P>
Referring to the explosion of technology in the media
industry, the Aga Khan challenged the view that "the developing
world in general and Africa in particular, may be left behind by
this revolution."
</P>
<P>
He argued that "it seems to me that societies which have
invested less in old technologies have the potential to propel
themselves into new technologies, provided they have the
commitment and resources to do so."
</P>
<P>
The Nation Group is the largest newspaper publishing company
in east and central Africa. It publishes five newspapers
including the recently launched regional weekly newspaper The
East African.
</P>
<P>
The Daily Nation has a circulation of 180,000 and the Sunday
Nation's sales are in excess of 220,000. All the three
newspapers are on the internet. 
</P>
</TEXT>
