<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kuwait Receives First UN Compensation Payment for </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, March 12 (Xinhua) -- Kuwait today said it
received the first payment of money from the United Nations
Compensation Committee for individual claimants who fell victims
to Iraq's occupation in 1990.
</P>
<P>
Kuwaiti Public Authority for the Assessment of Compensation
(PAAC) said in a statement that it received more than 11.3
million U.S. dollars Tuesday which would cover 3,482 claims of
category "A" (people who left Kuwait and Iraq ) and 1,061
claims of category "C" (individual losses less than 100,000
U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
Every claim would receive a maximum of 2,500 U.S. dollars
in accordance of UNCC decision, the statement said. Kuwait
welcomed the payment of the first installment which was made
possible due to the oil-for-food formula that allows Iraq to
sell 2 billion U.S. dollars of oil over a six-month period.
</P>
<P>
Thirty percent of Iraq's proceeds from the oil exports
under the formula goes to the UN compensation program. This
week UNCC made bank transfers amounting to 144 million U.S.
dollars to 63 governments representing 57,636 claimants.
</P>
<P>
Egypt is the largest beneficiary of the first installment
receiving 58.3 million U.S. dollars for 23,334 category "A"
claimants. Other large beneficiaries include Sri Lanka, India,
Bangladesh and Pakistan.
</P>
<P>
The compensation to Kuwaiti claimants would be paid in a
smooth manner with coordination with the ministry of finance,
the central bank, the ministry of justice and local banks,
PAAC's board chairman Khaled Ahmad Al-Modefh said.
</P>
<P>
He said the UNCC ratified 187,000 claims from Kuwait with
a total cost of 1.7 billion U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
Kuwait received the largest portion of a first symbolic
payment made in 1994 for 13.4 million U.S. dollars to
relatives of people who died as a result of the occupation.
</P>
<P>
"Kuwait also received some money from the UNCC before, but
it was small amount paid from frozen (Iraqi) assets," the
PAAC official said.
</P>
<P>
He said Kuwait welcomes this development and we hope that
the Kuwaitis and all other victims would be compensated.
</P>
<P>
Based on the assumption that the oil-for-food resolution is
extended in June 1997, it is expected that the second
installment payments could be made in August 1997. 
</P>
</TEXT>
