<HEADLINE> Pena Confirmed as U.S. Energy Secretary </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, March 12 (Xinhua) -- Federico Pena was confirmed as
energy secretary of the United States today by the Senate on a
vote of 99-1.
</P>
<P>
President Bill Clinton applauded the Senate for its "strong
vote of support" to the former mayor of Denver and transportation
secretary during Clinton's first term.
</P>
<P>
Both Democrats and Republicans said Pena was a man of integrity
who had shown an ability to resolve contentious issues during his
four years as transportation secretary.
</P>
<P>
The Energy and Natural Resources Committee voted last week,
19-0, to confirm Pena to the Cabinet post.
</P>
<P>
But the White House's opposition to a Senate bill for a
temporary nuclear waste storage facility in Nevada had held up
Pena's nomination for weeks.
</P>
<P>
Nevada's two senators strongly oppose the bill and Clinton has
promised to veto it.
</P>
<P>
With Pena's Senate approval, there are two more Clinton's
Cabinet nominees, Alexis Herman as labor secretary and Anthony
Lake as director of Central Intelligence Agency, to be confirmed
by Congress. 
</P>
