<HEADLINE> Camerounian PM Calls for Improved Health Care </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YAOUNDE, March 12 (Xinhua) -- Prime Minister of Cameroun Peter
Mafany Musonge today called on health experts in the country to
set up a solid base for the improvement of health care.
</P>
<P>
While opening the first national health forum at the Yaounde
Conference Center, Musonge said that health experts in Cameroun
have responsibilities to design an efficient health policy to
meet the challenges of the 21st century.
</P>
<P>
Musonge stressed that the well-being of Camerounians is at the
center of every development effort by the government.
</P>
<P>
He said the unethical practise problems within the health
sector have been aggravated by the present recession.
</P>
<P>
Efforts for the humanizing of health service, the provision of
essential drugs at proper prices, the involvement of health
personnel in the new health policy and the fight against
corruption in the sector are needed to form a solid base for the
improvement of health care.
</P>
<P>
Minister of Public Health Titus Adoza also called on
traditional doctors to demonstrate their commitment and
willingness to provide Camerounians with a creditable alternative
to western medicine, he said.
</P>
<P>
Among over 600 participants of the forum are health
consultants, traditional healers, provincial doctors, laboratary
technicians and opinion leaders from the country.
</P>
<P>
The three-day forum is expected to examine health problems
facing Cameroun and to propose strategies which will help improve
the health situation in the country.
</P>
<P>
Issues like the collaboration between the public and private
sectors, the financing of health services, the quality of health
service and health insurance will be discussed at the forum.
</P>
<P>
In Cameroun there is only one doctor for 10,000 inhabitants,
one pharmacy for 28,000, one dentist for 250,000
and one nurse for 2,100.  enditem

