<HEADLINE> Moi Inaugurates New Printing Plant </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, March 12 (Xinhua) -- Kenyan President Daniel arap Moi
this morning inaugurated a new printing plant of the Nation
Group set up on the outskirts of Nairobi.
</P>
<P>
A press release issued by the group said, "the new press is
the most advanced newspaper printing facility in Africa,
incorporating the latest state-of-the-art facilities."
</P>
<P>
The new press can print up to 60,000 copies an hour, 56 pages
in a single run and eight pages in full color, the release
noted.
</P>
<P>
The printing plant was built on a 10-acre plot at a cost of
13.5 million U.S. Dollars by the Nation Group which has five
newspapers in Kenya, namely, Daily Nation, Sunday Nation, the
East African, Taifa Leo and Taifa Jumapili.
</P>
<P>
The Aga Khan, Spiritual Leader of the Ismaili Muslims and the
principal shareholder of the Nation Group, attended the
inauguration ceremony.
</P>
<P>
At a luncheon in his honor hosted by President Moi on
Tuesday, the Aga Khan, who is on an official visit to Kenya, said that
the Aga Khan Development Network had decided to enlarge its
activities in Kenya and the east African region.
</P>
<P>
The Aga Khan announced that the network will invest up to 80
million U.S. Dollars to turn the Aga Khan Hospital in Nairobi
into one serving the whole east African region.
</P>
<P>
In the field of education, he said, the network will introduce
programs for school improvement activities which will have an
impact on over 200 schools in the country.
</P>
<P>
He also disclosed that the network would establish an
institution for advanced nursing in Kenya to cater for the entire
east Africa.
</P>
<P>
On the same occasion, President Moi noted that the Aga Khan
Development Network has for a long time supported Kenya's
development efforts by promoting socio-economic development in
various fields such as health, education and rural development.
</P>
<P>
The Kenyan leader said that the organization has also promoted
economic development initiatives in the fields of industry,
finance and tourism.
</P>
<P>
The network is a group of institutions working to improve
conditions and opportunities in specific regions of the
developing world, especially in east Africa.
</P>
<P>
The Aga Khan, who arrived here on March 10 following his visit
to Uganda, is scheduled to visit Tanzania during his eight-day
tour of east Africa. 
</P>
</TEXT>
