<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nepal's Group, ILO Reach Agreement on Child Labor </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, March 13 (Xinhua) -- Nepal's largest business group
and the International Labor Organization (ILO) signed an agreement
here today to implement a program to raise people's awareness
against child labor among employers of the country's industrial
sector.
</P>
<P>
Under the agreement, the Federation of Nepalese Chamber of
Commerce and Industry (FNCCI) promised to implement the program
with the objective to "sensitize" its members in various
industries on child labor and create public awareness on the
issue.
</P>
<P>
According to an ILO official, an increased output of carpet
industries in Asia's underdeveloped countries has raised the
demand for child labor, creating more problems relating to child
labor in the region.
</P>
<P>
Unofficial estimates show that Nepal has some five million
children directly or indirectly involved in different forms of
child labor, most of them working in places like carpet factories,
mines, and construction works.  
</P>
</TEXT>
