<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Malaysian Workers in Singapore Urged to Come Back </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, March 13 (Xinhua) -- Malaysian Human Resources
Minister Lim Ah Lek today urged Malaysian workers in Singapore to
return and work at home.
</P>
<P>
He made the call when commenting on the controversial remarks
Singapore Senior Minister Lee Kuan Yew made about Malaysia's Johor
State.
</P>
<P>
In a recent court affidavit, Lee described Johor as a place
"notorious for shootings, muggings and car-jackings."
</P>
<P>
Lim said the Singapore government does not appreciate the good
relationship between the two neighboring countries.
</P>
<P>
Malaysia, which itself is facing a labor shortage, need the
contributions of those who are working in Singapore and welcome
them to come back, the minister said after presenting scholarships
from the Sony group of companies in Malaysia.
</P>
<P>
"Malaysia would like them to work here rather than elsewhere
because we are having problems, especially now when the Singapore
government does not seem to value our good relationship," he said.
</P>
<P>
However, he said that his government is not forcing them to
come back but they should do so on their own initiative.
</P>
<P>
"We have pride, they should come back as they are not welcome
there (in Singapore) and that is not the first time he (Lee) said
that and that is not the way to build up a relationship between
the two countries," Lim said.
</P>
<P>
Malaysia has lost many trained workers to Singapore and yet the
Malaysian government never discouraged them from going there
despite a labor shortage, he said.
</P>
<P>
On the number of Malaysian workers in Singapore, Lim said he
did not have the figures as many of them work on their own and
are not required to register with the Manpower Department.
</P>
<P>
Lee Kuan Yew has made an apology to Malaysia in a statement
which was released today by his press secretary. 
</P>
</TEXT>
