<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kuwait Sells 40 Million New State-Owned Shares </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, March 13 (Xinhua) -- The Kuwait Investment
Authority (KIA), the only governmental agency managing public
stakes in state-owned companies, today sold in auction 40 million
shares of the Kuwaiti Company for Building and Repairing Ships in
a further effort to proceed with the privatization plan.
</P>
<P>
Hesham Al-Otaibi, Director General of the Kuwait Stock Exchange
through which the shares were sold, said the primary price of
each share was 206 fils (0.68 U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
He said the private International Investment Group Company
bought 10 million shares at a price of 208 fils (0.69 dollars) per
share while the Kuwait National Bank, a commercial bank taking
part in the auction on behalf of a group of investors, bought the
other 30 million shares at a cost of 206 fils (0.68 dollars) per
share.
</P>
<P>
The amount of shares sold today constitutes 30 percent of the
company's total shares. The KIA and the Kuwaiti Oil Tankers
Company, the country's only state-owned oil transporting company,
together hold 108 million shares of the company, accounting for
81 percent of the company's total shares.
</P>
<P>
The auction was within the framework of the KIA's policy
to promote private investments.
</P>
<P>
Kuwait so far has raised about 600 million dinars (about 2
billion dollars) from its privatization plan launched in 1994
which is designed to widen the investor base, reduce state
economic controls and boost efficiency.
</P>
<P>
Most of the shares were sold off through auctions and public
subscriptions.
</P>
<P>
KIA director-general Ali Al-Bader said last December that the
authority, which had already sold its stake in about 15 Kuwaiti
firms, is in charge of a plan to sell state holdings in about 60
local firms and to prepare for a second phase to end state
involvement in some public services like water, electricity and
telecommunications.
</P>
<P>
Participation in Kuwait's privatization plan is exclusive to
nationals of the Gulf Cooperation Council states including Saudi
Arabia, the United Arab Emirates, Qatar, Oman, Bahrain and
Kuwait.
</P>
<P>
Another 65 million shares of the company would be offered to
public subscription after the March auction at a rate yet to be
decided, the KIA official said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
