<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Brain Cells Cultivated in Space </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 13 (Xinhua) -- Active brain cells have been
cultivated in a Chinese satellite some 300 km away from the earth.
</P>
<P>
Scientists from the Chinese Academy of Sciences said here today
that the achievement indicates that China has met the advanced
world standard in biological experiments in space.
</P>
<P>
A total of 33 different species of bio-products, weighing 91
kg, were put into a satellite launched on October 20, 1996, for a
cultivation experiment.
</P>
<P>
After the satellite's return, Chinese scientists spent three
months studying the results, which have shown that China has for
the first time obtained in-space active brain cells, solid seaweed
with a high resistance to salt, and high-quality fungi.
</P>
<P>
Other successful experiments proved that high-grade plants can
sprout and grow, and that insects can breed in space.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese scientists were also excited to find fixed cells of
different micro seaweeds had grown in space, which suggests a
bright future for the development of biological reactors in space.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
