<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UN Sanctions Committee Approves 11 Contracts on </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, March 13 (Xinhua) -- The U.N. Security Council
Sanctions Committee has approved 11 more contracts on selling
Iraqi oil in exchange for food and medicine, bringing the total
number of the approved contracts to 26, local media reported today.
</P>
<P>
The official Iraqi News Agency quoted Iraqi Minister of
Commerce Mohammed Mehdi Saleh saying that the new contracts
involved wheat, rice, cereals, tea and detergents.
</P>
<P>
He said that these contracts had previously been stricken with
France, Jordan, Vietnam Indonesia, Turkey and Pakistan.
</P>
<P>
Iraq has so far submitted 240 contracts to the U.N. Security
Council Sanctions Committee for approval since Iraq was allowed to
export a limited amount of oil last December.
</P>
<P>
For several times, Iraq has complained that the U.N. Security
Council Sanctions Committee delayed its approval of the contracts
it concluded with other countries for selling oil for food and
medical supplies in accordance with a relevant memorandum of
understanding signed between the two sides. 
</P>
</TEXT>
