<DOCNO> XIE19970313.0097 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lee Kuan Yew Makes Apology to Malaysia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, March 13 (Xinhua) -- Singapore's Senior Minister Lee
Kuan Yew today apologized to Malaysia for his controversial
remarks on Johor, a southern state of Malaysia.
</P>
<P>
In a written statement distributed this evening, Lee's press
secretary said that the senior minister "had no intention to cause
offense" in the sworn affidavit he made on January 27 in a court
hearing on defamation cases against opposition Workers' Party
member Tang Liang Hong.
</P>
<P>
Lee said: "I was baffled. He (Tang) claimed his life was under
threat. But, of all places, he went to Johor. That place is
notorious for shootings, muggings and car-jackings. It does not
make sense for a person who claims to be fearful for his life to
go to a place like Johor."
</P>
<P>
This angered Malaysia and Malaysian Foreign Minister Datuk
Abdullah Ahmad Badawi demanded Wednesday that Lee apologize for
the "callous" statement.
</P>
<P>
Lee's press secretary explained: "The Senior Minister has not
been to Johor since he stepped down as Prime Minister in
1990....It was his perception based on reports he had read in the
press."
</P>
<P>
He said said Lee made the remarks not in open court and it was
"unfortunate" that it became public by the way the litigation
developed.
</P>
<P>
"The affidavit sought to rebut the reasons Tang had given for
leaving Singapore for Johor Baru immediately after the general
election," which was held on January 2.
</P>
<P>
However, the press secretary said, the public was confused over
the terms and effect of the Mareva injunction. As a result, the
parties applied and the judge ordered open court hearings so that
the public would have the facts.
</P>
<P>
Tang also asked for an open court hearing when he sought to
challenge the impartiality of the judge, he noted.
</P>
<P>
"This meant that the affidavit would now be discussed in open
Court. As a result it has now been reported in the press. This was
not anticipated when Mr Lee first applied for the Mareva."
</P>
<P>
"He had no intention that his affidavit made in support of
court proceedings in Chambers should affect the good relations
between Malaysia and Singapore," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
