<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Desert-Based Aerospace Town Turned into Oasis </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LANZHOU, March 13 (Xinhua) -- Every year, a large number of
outsiders, both Chinese and foreigners, visit the China Jiuquan
Satellite Launching Base in Gansu Province in northwest China.
</P>
<P>
Located in a vast desert, the small town that surrounds the
base holds a certain appeal for travelers, with lush greenery and
flowers blooming everywhere. The only bleakness on the horizon is
a bald, brown mountain on the city's west side.
</P>
<P>
Thanks to the efforts of local residents, most of whom are
employed in the country's aerospace industry, the desert town has
been turned into an oasis.
</P>
<P>
According to local officials, the base is one of the oldest and
largest in the country to conduct experimental satellite and
missile launches, including "Dongfanghong No. 1," the country's
first satellite sent into orbit in April, 1969.
</P>
<P>
The base was first called "Dongfeng." Chinese President Jiang
Zemin inscribed "Dongfeng Aerospace Town" during a visit in 1992.
</P>
<P>
Some locals recall that when tens of thousands of soldiers came
to build the base, it was nothing but endless desert, barren save
for spotty tufts of grass blowing in the dry wind.
</P>
<P>
Kang Xiuying, a retired teacher from a local kindergarten who
has spent most of her life there, said that when they first
arrived, the salt and soda content in the soil was so high that
people had to wrap their feet and legs with cloth to prevent their
skin from becoming parched and cracked.
</P>
<P>
In summer, she recalled, the scorching cobblestones burned
people's feet, even through the soles of their shoes. The bone-dry
air caused chronic chapped lips and nosebleeds, and everyone had a
suntan.
</P>
<P>
The stark reality of life in the desert has prompted local
residents, soldiers and officers alike, to consider the issue of
afforestation.
</P>
<P>
Young people now are told repeatedly not to damage
trees. Retired driver Zhang Zhan'ao, like many other residents in
the town, has planted flowers and fruit trees in his courtyard.
</P>
<P>
Large forested and grassy areas have been built up on the edge
of the town, while large tracts of farmlands have been cultivated
nearby. A reservoir capable of storing 18 million cubic meters
lies beside the paddy and wheat fields.
</P>
<P>
In the past, pilots flying overhead had trouble seeing the base
below, as the small town blended into the desert due to its lack
of green. Now, with a green coverage of 61 percent, the base is
easily detected from the sky.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970313.0100 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nigeria Hopes to Improve Ties With Canada </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, March 13 (Xinhua) -- The Foreign Ministry today reacted
quickly toward Canada's decision to suspend diplomatic activities
in Nigeria, saying it is looking forward to an earlier resumption
of the normal operations of the Canadian high commission.
</P>
<P>
The Canadian government on Wednesday announced the temporary
suspension of operations at the Canadian High Commission in Lagos
due to "safety concerns".
</P>
<P>
However, the suspension does not mean that Nigeria will break
off bilateral diplomatic relations with Canada, a Foreign
Ministry spokesman said this morning.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman described it as "groundless" that the Canadians
claimed officials at the high commission or embassy have not been
given the security assurances by the Nigerian side.
</P>
<P>
According to a statement of the Canadian foreign ministry on
Wednesday, the Canadian embassy in Lagos has been without a
security officer since last December and efforts by Canada to
send a replacement have been blocked by the failure of the
Nigerian government to issue a visa.
</P>
<P>
But this claim is "absolutely groundless," said the Nigerian
spokesman, adding that the Nigerian government hopes Canada will
resume the normal operations of its high commission as early as
possible.
</P>
<P>
Nigeria close down its high commission in Canada last
September in an adjustment of its diplomatic missions and
personnel abroad due to the short of fund.
</P>
<P>
The move, however, is seen by observers as sort of retaliation
to Canada's tough stand against Nigeria.
</P>
<P>
Relations between the two countries have been fraught with
diplomatic hiccups following Canada's consistent calls for
sanctions against Nigeria over its human rights record which
forced the Commonwealth to suspend Nigeria in November 1995.
</P>
<P>
According to diplomatic sources, Canada has since maintained a
hostile attitude toward Nigeria, especially within the
Commonwealth Ministerial Action Group (CMAG), established for
monitoring human rights situation in its African member states.
</P>
<P>
Last June, when CMAG decided not to impose further sanctions
against Nigeria, Canada, a member of CMAG, said it was going
ahead for some more sanctions unilaterally.
</P>
<P>
With the temporary closure of the Canadian high commission in
Nigeria, observers here said there might be an even glimmer
future between the two countries. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
