<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China to Add 2,100 Airliners in 20 Years </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 13 (Xinhua) -- China's passenger turnover
through air transport is expected to increase by 11.5 percent
annually in the coming 20 years, bringing the need for an
additional 2,100 planes by the year 2015.
</P>
<P>
About 1,700 large and medium-sized aircraft should be added by
then, according to an annual report by the China Aviation
Industrial Corporation under the Civil Aviation Administration of
China.
</P>
<P>
The report says that with the growth of China's economic
strength, civil aviation will also develop quickly. Although the
yearly increase in air transport is lower than 23.4 percent for
the Eighth Five-Year Plan (1991-1995), it will be much higher than
the world average in the next 20 years.
</P>
<P>
By 2015, 150-seat airliners will still account for most of the
country's aviation fleet, followed by 200-seat and 300-seat
airplanes, the report predicts.
</P>
<P>
The Annual Report on Predictions for China's Airline Market was
first published in 1991, and is updated each year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
