<HEADLINE> China to Send Cyclists to Train in France </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 13 (Xinhua) -- China will send cyclists to
France where they will be trained by top French coaches, the
Chinese Cycling Association (CCA) announced on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Visiting officials from the French Cycling Association had
reached initial agreement with their Chinese counterparts here
upon the exchange program in cycling between the two countries,
the CCA said.
</P>
<P>
According to the agreement, China will invite French cyclists
to race at this year's Chinese National Championships and the Tour
of Silk Road cycling meet, hire a French coach in the women's
sprint event to help China prepare for the 1998 Asian Games.
</P>
<P>
France will invite Chinese moutain bikers to compete in the
Tour de France mountain bike event and support China in its bids
to stage a leg in the 1999 Mountain Bike World Cup series and
World Junior Cycling Championships in 2000.
</P>
<P>
But the details of the cooperation have yet to be finalised,
they said.
</P>
<P>
The CCA said the cooperation will help tremendously in its
long-term development plan which aims at winning a cycling medal
at the Sydney Olympic Games in 2000 and clinching a gold medal at
the 2004 Olympics.
</P>
<P>
The best result that China had at the Olympics was a seventh
place while France won five cycling golds at Atlanta last summer.
</P>
</TEXT>
