<HEADLINE> Iran Rejects Israeli Allegation on Military </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, March 13 (Xinhua) -- The Iranian military authorities
today rejected an allegation by Israeli military authorities
that Iran is trying to purchase ballistic missiles.
</P>
<P>
Iran does not need to "utilize non-conventional weapons and
it procures its needs from domestic sources," a high-ranking
military official was quoted by the state-run news agency IRNA
as saying.
</P>
<P>
However, the report did not give the name and identity
of the military official.
</P>
<P>
An anonymous Israeli military official in Moscow, Russia,
Monday reportedly threatened that Israel will act to prevent
arming Iran with ballistic missiles if persuasion fails to
do the job.
</P>
<P>
The Iranian military authorities responded by saying that such
allegations are raised to shift the crisis elsewhere from the
territories the Jewish state has occupied and these attempts are
doomed to fail, according to the IRNA.
</P>
<P>
The Iranian official described the conventional military
cooperation between Iran and other countries as a routine
practice at an international level.
</P>
<P>
He said that Iran has repeatedly expressed its interest in
promotion of its defensive cooperation in the Gulf and with
neighboring countries and has taken steps in this direction.
</P>
