<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-13 14:19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Netanyahu Condemns Israeli-Jordanian Border </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, March 13 (Xinhua) -- Israeli Prime Minister Binyamin
Netanyahu condemned shooting that occurred today near the
Israeli-Jordanian boder in which seven Israeli students were
killed and a dozen others injured.
</P>
<P>
A Jordanian soldier opened fired without provocation at a
group of Israeli school girls from Beit Shemesh of central
Israel, who were on a school outing in the scenic Naharayim
area on the Jordanian side of the Jordan Valley.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu said that any kind of violence against the innocent
was unacceptable in whatever terms and should be rejected. He said
nothing could legitimatize violence, stressing that "there is no
greater danger (than violence) to the peace process."
</P>
<P>
"We can have disagreements, they are inevitable in any kind of
process and negotiation. But we cannot pursue peace unless we
pursue it peacefully," he said, referring to the current disputes
between Israel and Arab neighbors.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu urged the Jordanian government to bring those guilty
to trial and to investigate how this incident took place.
</P>
<P>
Israel radio reported Jordanian King Hussein had telephoned
Israeli President Ezer Weizman to express his shock and sorrow
over the killing, and to offer his condolences to families
of the victims. The monarch promised that he would do
everything possible to calm the current tense situation.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Jordanian Prime Minister Abdul Karim Kabariti has
sent an expert team to investigate the incident. He also expressed
condolences to the Israeli government and the families of the
victims.
</P>
<P>
The shooting took place near the Israeli-Jordanian border,
which has been relatively calm since the two sides signed a peace
treaty in 1994. Naharayim is an scenic enclave in the Jordan
Valley which was returned to Jordan by Israel under the 1994 peace
treaty, but Israelis still have full access to the area for
sightseeings.
</P>
<P>
Today's incident also occurred during a time of rising tension
between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
Hussein and Netanyahu recently exchanged angry letters over the
current Israeli-Palestinian peace deadlock. Hussein strongly
criticized Israeli government for endangering the peace process
with its hardline policies. 
</P>
</TEXT>
