<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Jordanian King Condemns Shooting Incident </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMMAN, March 13 (Xinhua) -- Jordanian King Hussein
telephoned Israeli Prime Minister Binyamin Netanyahu and condemned
today's shooting incident near the Israel-Jordan border during
which seven were killed and a dozen of others injured.
</P>
<P>
The king, who is on an official visit to London, also offered
his condolences to families of the victims, Jordan's Petra news
agency reported.
</P>
<P>
A Jordanian soldier opened fire to a van carrying Israeli
school girls in the northwestern town of Bahulha town, the Petra
report said, adding the reason of the firing is not clear.
</P>
<P>
Petra said the soldier was arrested.
</P>
<P>
The shooting took place in the Naharayim area near the
Israeli-Jordanian border, which has been relatively calm since the
two sides signed a peace treaty in 1994.
</P>
<P>
Naharayim is an scenic enclave in the Jordan Valley which was
returned to Jordan by Israel under the 1994 peace treaty, but
Israelis still have full access to the area for sightseeings.
</P>
<P>
Hussein, after calling Netanyahu, decided to delay his visit to
the United States scheduled on March 18 and come back from London
to settle the issue.
</P>
<P>
Jordanian Crown Prince Hassan Ibn Talal and Prime Minister
Abdul Karim Kabariti also went to the hospital where the injured
are treated and expressed sympathy to them. 
</P>
</TEXT>
