<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Improving Consumer Rights Protection </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, February 13 (Xinhua) -- China has established a basic
legal framework for protecting consumer rights and interests that
is in step with the substantial growth in consumer goods.
</P>
<P>
A spokesman for the State Statistics Bureau said today that
China's work on legal affairs for safeguarding consumer rights and
interests has improved steadily since China initiated the reform
and opening-up policy in the late 1970s.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman said that China has approved over 200 laws and
regulations related to economic affairs, more than 60 of which are
directly associated with consumer rights and interests.
</P>
<P>
These include the "Law on the Protection of Consumers' Rights
and Interests," the "Law against Unfair Competition" and laws on
product quality and food hygiene.
</P>
<P>
Providing further protection are the consumer groups which have
sprung up across the country. The China National Consumers'
Association, founded in 1984, has opened branches in provinces,
cities and counties. Last year, it received half a million
complaints and resolved 88.7 percent of them, recovering more than
300 million yuan in losses.
</P>
<P>
However, he said, China still has much to do to protect the
rights and interests of consumers, partly because consumers don't
know how to protect themselves.
</P>
<P>
A survey conducted jointly by the State Statistics Bureau, the
People's Bank of China, the All-China Federation of Trade Unions
and ministries of Labor, Public Health and Civil Affairs in
December 1996-January 1997 shows that nearly a quarter of the
Chinese urban consumers, or some 50 million, reported abuses of
their rights last year, involving a loss of about 6.8 billion yuan.
</P>
<P>
The survey finds that only 22.3 percent these consumers voiced
their complaints; nearly 70 percent accepted their situation
without coming forward.
</P>
<P>
Some of those who did seek justice took their gripes back to
the shops where they purchased the goods or to other service
outlets. Some complained to consumers' associations or contacted
the manufacturers. Only 1.1 percent took legal action.
</P>
<P>
The survey finds that purchase of fake or inferior quality
products is the major source of abuse to consumers' rights and
interests.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
