<BODY>
<HEADLINE> World's Interest High in 4th Hortec Fair in Kenya </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, March 13 (Xinhua) -- The East Africa's fourth
International Horticultural Trade Exhibition opened in downtown
Nairobi today, attracting a considerable number of overseas
horticultural buyers, dealers and auctioneers.
</P>
<P>
Interest in the three-day exhibition is so high that all
available stand space at the Kenyatta International Conference
Center had been snapped up by November.
</P>
<P>
Among more than 120 participants of the 1997 show are those
from South Africa, France, the Netherlands, Israel, Germany,
Britain and Spain.
</P>
<P>
Displays range from root stock, seeds, fertilizers,
agro-chemicals and greenhouses to power generations and water
pumping equipment, cold storage and transport.
</P>
<P>
Cut flowers, in various delicate colors and shapes, are in
abundance there, as overseas and local suppliers of root stock
display their end products.
</P>
<P>
A series of seminars on Kenya's horticultural industry will be
held during the trade fair, sponsored by the Fresh Produce
Exporters Association of Kenya (FPEAK).
</P>
<P>
Kenya has been rated internationally over recent years as a
major supplier of flowers and vegetables, notably cut flowers,
fresh green beans, snow peas and avocados.
</P>
<P>
Fresh produce exports are the fourth foreign exchange earner
after tourism, tea and coffee for this eastern African country,
said Darius Mbela, the minister of agriculture, livestock
development, at the beginning of the exhibition.
</P>
<P>
He vowed the government will continue to support the industry
through research work, the provision of extension services as
well as the development of an enabling policy framework.
</P>
<P>
Kenyan horticultural exports reached 83,496 tons in 1996, up
16.4 percent from the previous year, according to data from
FPEAK.
</P>
<P>
The country is expecting to export more than 100,000 tons of
horticultural products annually by the turn of the century, local
reports said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
