<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Jobless Climbs, Full-Time Jobs Fall Down in Australia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, March 13 (Xinhua) -- Australia's jobless rate last
month climbed to 8.8 from 8.5 percent, as the proportion of
full-time work to total employment fell to its lowest level on
record.
</P>
<P>
The Australian Bureau of Statistics (ABS) in its bulletin
released today said 19,900 people became unemployed in February,
pushing the jobless rate to its highest level since last October.
</P>
<P>
Following continued strong growth in part-time positions in the
past year, the ratio of full-time work to total employment fell to
a record low of 74.6 percent.
</P>
<P>
Commenting on the unemployment rate, Prime Minister John Howard
said that "there are a number of things we've already done which,
over time, ought to lift economic growth."
</P>
<P>
"We have changed the industrial system. Business investment is
running at a historically high level and we have very low rates of
inflation. Now all of those things are benign and positive for
economic growth," he told reporters in Sydney.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to his party supporters yesterday, he said that
economic growth would need to accelerate from the present level of
about 3.5 percent to between 4 and 4.5 percent before the jobless
rate could be substantially reduced.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
