<HEADLINE> Indian Government Takes Measures for Aircraft Safety </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, March 13 (Xinhua) -- India's Minister for Civil
Aviation C.M. Ibrahim said today that S mode transponders are
being installed in all Indian airlines and Air India aircraft as
an additional precautionary system for the safety of planes.
</P>
<P>
Installation of the facilities would be completed by Indian
airlines by December 1997 and Air India by June 1997, he said
while replying to a question at the lower house of parliament
here.
</P>
<P>
The decision to install S mode transponders was taken as a
follow-up measure after the mid-air collision near New Delhi,
capital of India, last year killing about 350 people, he said.
</P>
<P>
A special committee was set up since the accident and a task
force was also set up later to act on the recommendations of the
committee and propose alternatives where necessary, he added.
</P>
</TEXT>
