<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Refutes US Human Rights Reports (3) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The commentary says that the Chinese state, in fact, protects
the freedom of religion of the citizens and their normal religious
activities in accordance with the law. No one will be punished
just for religious beliefs or for normal religious activities. At
the same time, people cannot avoid penalties for criminal
activities simply because they believe in religion or flaunt the
banner of religion.
</P>
<P>
The third part of the commentary criticizes the "Reports" for
using a lot of space to accuse China of having no freedom of
speech, of the press, or of information in order to vilify China.
</P>
<P>
It is common knowledge that there can be no freedom of speech,
of the press, or of information in the world without some limits,
the commentary notes.
</P>
<P>
China's lawful limits to freedom of speech, the press, and
information fully conform to the spirit of the international
convention on human rights and to international practice, it says.
</P>
<P>
As a matter of fact, the commentary notes, the "Reports" is not
concerned about the question of whether Chinese citizens really
enjoy the freedom of speech, of the press, or information. Any
politically unprejudiced person would not deny that freedoms,
including the speech, press and information freedoms that the
Chinese people enjoy today greatly surpass those of any periods of
Chinese history.
</P>
<P>
The majority of Chinese people now have many more individual
freedoms than ever before, Anthony Saich, representative of the
Ford Foundation in charge of China affairs said in February, 1997,
The commentary notes.
</P>
<P>
Former US President George Bush said on February 24, 1997 that
Chinese citizens today have more human rights and individual
freedoms than at the time he left the country in 1975, according
to the commentary.
</P>
<P>
In its last part, the commentary states with numerous facts
that during the past year, great improvements were made in China's
human rights situation. In 1996, China's economy achieved
sustained, rapid and healthy growth, democratic and legislative
construction was obviously enhanced, and people's rights to exist
and develop and other human rights further improved.
</P>
<P>
To reach its anti-China, anti-Communism aims, the "Reports"
ignore the facts and describe China, which is constantly
developing, as a country with worsening human rights conditions,
the commentary says.
</P>
<P>
It says that using human rights to carry out public opinion
struggle against China is a full manifestation of the stubborn
Cold War mentality of the United States.
</P>
<P>
The "Reports", started in the days of Cold War as part of its
"human rights diplomacy", was actually used to meet Cold War
political demands, it stressed.
</P>
<P>
The commentary notes that after the ending of the Cold War, the
United States takes socialist China, which persists in its own
road of development, as its imaginary enemy, and frequently
attacks China by using the issue of human rights.
</P>
<P>
The annual human rights "Reports" of the US State Department
have therefore become an important tool for opposing China,
vilifying China, and interfering in the internal affairs of China,
it says. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
