<DOCNO> XIE19970313.0129 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> More Arms Uncovered in Kromah's Country Home </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, March 13 (Xinhua) -- The west African peacekeeping
force, known as ECOMOG, reported on Wednesday the discovery of
more weapons at another home of former Liberian warlord Alhaji
Kromah outside Monrovia, capital of Liberia.
</P>
<P>
Kromah, leader of the defunct ULIMO-K warring faction, has
been put under house arrest since ECOMOG troops found a big
quantity of arms at his residence in Monrovia last Friday with
his fellow Mandingo fighters claiming it a plot against him by
protest actions.
</P>
<P>
A report reaching here today quoted ECOMOG sources as saying
that troops again discovered scores of heavy calibre guns, rocket
propelled grenade guns and bombs from Kromah's residence in
Voinjama in Loffa County, some 260 km north of Monrovia.
</P>
<P>
A container full of rocket-propelled grenade bombs was also
taken from the ULIMO-K barracks in the town.
</P>
<P>
The search was conducted following information provided by
residents of Loffa County, according to a statement issued on
Wednesday after a meeting between ECOMOG Force Commander
Major-General Victor Malu and members of the International
Mediatio Committee of Ambassadors and United Nations officials.
</P>
<P>
The Liberian Justice Ministry said earlier this week that
Kromah will appear before a magistrate to answer charges of
illegally stashing arms against him, as ECOMOG has completed
investigation.
</P>
<P>
On Wednesday, a local newspaper owned by Kromah, The National,
reported that he was due to appear in court before the weekend.
</P>
<P>
Since the end of a week-long grace period for former faction
fighters to surrender their arms after the January 31 deadline,
ECOMOG has recovered some 920 weapons and large quantities of
ammunition from various parts of Liberia, Malu said at
Wednesday's meeting.
</P>
<P>
Malu had announced before the deadline that after that date
ECOMOG will hunt the hidden arms in the country and any one
caught with weapons will be treated as common criminal. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
