<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Refutes US Human Rights Reports (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 13 (Xinhua) -- The Information Office of China's
State Council published a commentary today refuting the United
States' attempt to provoke a confrontation and interfere in
China's internal affairs under the pretext of human rights.
</P>
<P>
The commentary notes that on January 30, 1997, the US State
Department released its "Country Reports on Human Rights Practices
for 1996", in which it commented improperly on the human rights
situation in 194 countries and regions.
</P>
<P>
It says the "China part" of the "Reports" continues to spread
slanderous rumors against China in disregard of the Chinese
people's strong opposition in the past years, thus laying bare the
attempt of the "Reports" to create confrontation and interfere in
China's internal affairs by using the pretext of human rights.
</P>
<P>
The commentary with about 8,000 words, entitled "Another act of
creating confrontation by using the pretext of human rights,"
falls into four parts.
</P>
<P>
In the first part, the commentary points out that one of the
major characteristics of the US State Department's "Reports" is to
attempt to mislead the public by using materials that were proven
worthless long ago, and tried to turn lies into truth by repeating
them.
</P>
<P>
It says that most of the "new" materials and cases provided by
the "Reports" are fabricated and false.
</P>
<P>
For instance, the "Reports" alleged that Ngawang Choephel, a
foreign scholar visiting Tibet, was detained by Chinese
authorities for making a documentary about Tibetan performing
arts, and was sentenced to 18 years in prison.
</P>
<P>
The commentary says that the fact is that the 30-year-old
Ngawang Choephel entered China in June, 1995, having been sent by
the Dalai Lama clique to engage in intelligence activities under
the guise of collecting materials on the Tibetan performing arts,
using funding and equipment provided by a foreign country.
</P>
<P>
During his stay in Tibet, he collected information in Lhasa,
Shannan, Nyingchi and Xigaze by using methods conforming to the
"information collection plan" he drafted before the visit, the
commentary notes.
</P>
<P>
Having gained sufficient evidence of Nagawang Choephel's
espionage activities, the commentary says, China's public security
departments arrested him in accordance with the law, and Nagawang
Choephel made a full confession of his espionage
activities.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
