<DOCNO> XIE19970313.0136 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> HK Papers Highlight Budget Straddling Handover </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, March 13 (Xinhua) -- All Hong Kong newspapers today
devoted full pages to Hong Kong's 1997-98 financial budget, which
was unfolded Wednesday by Financial Secretary Donald Tsang
Yam-kuen.
</P>
<P>
Hong Kong Commercial Daily said in today's commentary that the
budget, entitled "Continuity in a Time of Change," is a unique
one that is to straddle the handover on July 1, 1997, when China
resumes the exercise of its sovereignty over Hong Kong. The budget
is unique for it was based on consensus reached between China and
Britain through negotiations of the Sino-British Joint Liaison
Group.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese paper said that the budget is "steady and prudent"
because it follows strictly the traditional principle of "living
within one's means" and complies with the provisions of the Basic
Law, the constitutional document of Hong Kong after July 1, 1997.
</P>
<P>
The Express News said in a commentary that the new budget
basically makes everybody happy and is conducive to the smooth
transition. The huge public wealth will lay a solid foundation for
the economic development of Hong Kong after the handover, says
the paper.
</P>
<P>
The Financial Secretary forecast on Wednesday that as Hong
Kong becomes a Special Administrative Region of China, it will
have total reserves of around 330 billion HK dollars (42.3
billion US dollars).
</P>
<P>
Ta Kung Pao commented that the budget shoulders a historic
mission. On the one hand, it must respond to the far-reaching
significance of the resumption of the exercise of China's
sovereignty, and on the other hand, it must respond to the
establishment of the Hong Kong Special Administrative Region
(HKSAR).
</P>
<P>
The Chinese daily said that many Hong Kong people and social
groups have expressed their satisfactions with the new budget,
which, they believe, will help to increase Hong Kong people's
confidence, and help the smooth transition and future development
of Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
Wen Wei Po's commentary said that the budget should be
scrutinized by the Provisional Legislative Council (PLC), the
interim legislature of the HKSAR.
</P>
<P>
The budget covers the last three months under the British rule
and the first nine months of the Hong Kong Special Administrative
Region (HKSAR). The 1997-98 financial year runs from April 1,
1997, to March 31, 1998.  
</P>
</TEXT>
