<HEADLINE> HK to Stage Int'l Seminar on Sports Marketing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, March 13 (Xinhua) -- Some of the most important and
influential leaders in the world of sports will address an
international seminar in Hong Kong in June on sports marketing in
the next century, organizers announced here Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Twelve sports leaders from around the world will provide their
views on the future direction of sports at the two-day seminar
named "Marketing of Sports in the 21st Century."
</P>
<P>
"This is the most ambitious and prestigious conference the SDB
has ever organized," Andrew Ma, chief executive of the Hong Kong
Sports Development Board (SDB), told a press conference.
</P>
<P>
"We have seen, in the last 10 years or so, marketing has played
an increasingly important role in the world of sports. The
Olympics, the World Cup, the Asian Games and the Commonwealth
Games and other big sporting spectacles, once organized on a
largely amateur basis, have been transformed into multi-million
dollar extravaganzas.
</P>
<P>
"As more money and sponsorship have been poured into sports,
sports and business have been irrevocably intertwined," he added.
</P>
<P>
The speakers will offer their views on the future economic,
social and political impacts on sports, Ma said.
</P>
<P>
Among them are Michael Payne, marketing director of the
International Olympic Committee, Wei Jizhong, secretary-general of
the Chinese Olympic Committee, and Christopher Renner, general
manager of ISL, Asia Pacific, who oversees marketing of Hong
Kong's professional football league and sponsorship programs for
Hong Kong's Amateur Sports Federation and Olympic Committee.
</P>
<P>
"What more opportune time than now, with the approach of a new
millennium, to examine this question. And what more appropriate a
 place than Hong Kong, on the verge of an historical and exciting
handover to China, to play host to this conference," the SDB chief
said.
</P>
<P>
The Conference scheduled for June 13-14 is organized by the SDB
in conjunction with the Hong Kong Tourist Association and the Hong
Kong Dragon Boat Association.  
</P>
