<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> FM Spokesman Refuted US Bill on Hong Kong </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 13 (Xinhua) -- China voiced its strong
opposition to US interference in China's internal affairs here
today.
</P>
<P>
It is reported that the US House of Representatives recently
approved a bill regarding Hong Kong, asking China to honor the
Sino-British Joint declaration and accusing China of setting up
the Provisional Legislative Council of Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
Asked to comment on the report at a routine press conference
here today, Chinese Foreign Ministry Spokesman Cui Tiankai said
that there are some people in the US Congress who know nothing
about the reality in Hong Kong and have no idea about China's Hong
Kong Policy. However, he added, without having any necessary
in-depth study, they went so far as to approve some so-called bill
that gratuitously questions whether China will comply with the
Sino-British Joint Declaration after July 1, 1997, incites
suspicions about China's sincerity and determination for
implementing its relevant policies, and threatens that the US
would take measures to alter the relevant US practices in the case
that Hong Kong's high level of autonomy and the American political
and economic interests there are damaged after July 1, 1997.
</P>
<P>
"We strongly oppose and will absolutely not accept such a
wrongful move of grossly interfering in China's internal affairs,"
Cui stated.
</P>
<P>
The issue of Hong Kong is the business between the Chinese and
British governments before July 1, 1997, and will be China's
domestic affairs after Hong Kong's return to the motherland, he
said, adding that no foreign government or organization has the
right to meddle in Hong Kong affairs.
</P>
<P>
Now that Hong Kong's return to its motherland is already a
certainty, which is the general wish of the people, the United
States ought to try and play a positive role for the benefit of
Hong Kong's smooth transition and long-term prosperity and
stability, Cui said. "This will not only meet China's interests,
but also serve the US fundamental interests," he noted.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970313.0148 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Major News Items in Leading Nigerian Newspapers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, March 13 (Xinhua) -- The following are major news items
in leading Nigerian newspapers today.
</P>
<P>
Daily Times
</P>
<P>
-- The rift between the Nigerian Liquefied Natural Gas (NLNG)
Ltd and ENEL of Italy over the European company's pull-out of a
multi-billion-U.S.-dollar gas purchase contract, took a new turn
on Wednesday when the government issued a strong warning to the
NLNG not to tamper with the Italian firm's volume of gas.
