<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China to become World's Second Largest PC Market </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, March 13 (Xinhua) -- Sales of personal computers in
China will reach eight to ten million units in 2000, making the
country the world's second largest PC market after Japan, a local
electronics expert predicts.
</P>
<P>
Zhou Muchang, head of the Ministry of Electronics Industry's
Computer and Microelectronics Research Center, who made the remark
in an interview with Xinhua, says that China's computer industry
experienced "certain substantial changes" last year.
</P>
<P>
Business in the computer and related industries was 92 billion
yuan last year, up nearly 50 percent from 1995, and hardware sales
were worth 71.5 billion yuan, an increase of 52 percent. Software
products posted sales of 9.2 billion yuan, up 35.3 percent, while
other information services amounted to 11.3 billion yuan, a rise
of almost 47 percent.
</P>
<P>
"Now fifth worldwide, China's share of the global market
increased from 0.5 percent some years ago to two percent last
year," said Zhou.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, mass production of computer components has allowed
PC sellers to cut costs by a bigger margin than ever. "Three
computer parts and components production centers have sprung up in
the Pearl River Delta, the Yangtze River Valley, and the Bohai Sea
Rim, which includes Beijing and Tianjin," Zhou said.
</P>
<P>
Local computers can now keep up with international developments
and promote their own brand-name products. Major producers,
including Legend, Great Wall, Founder, and Donghai, now compete
with overseas corporations, including such famous brands as IBM,
Compaq, and Hewllet Packard. Last year Chinese producers even
launched price-cutting campaigns to grab a larger share from
overseas rivals.
</P>
<P>
According to Zhou, Chinese producers had a 26 percent market
share, and "the development trend this year will go further
upward," he said. Foreign PCs still have 44 percent of the
market. The rest were "clone products," he said.
</P>
<P>
New technical gadgets have also become popular in
China. ChinaNet, which is connected to Internet, saw the number of
users jump from 3,000 in 1995 to more than 100,000 last year, Zhou
said. Foreign technology and equipment providers are now taking a
closer look at the burgeoning market in China, he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
