<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese City Dealing With Robberies of Ancient Tombs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WUHAN, March 13 (Xinhua) -- Jinzhou city in central China's
Hubei Province caught 44 tomb robbers over the past few years and
has sentenced 14 to prison.
</P>
<P>
Jinzhou, a state level historical city, has some 800 ancient
tombs marking with dune-like pile of earth, including those of
kings of the Chu State in the Spring and Autumn Period (770-476
BC).
</P>
<P>
To protect the tombs from an increasing number of robberies in
the past few years, the city initiated a responsibility system,
involving 861 households in 55 villages in five townships where
there are a large number of ancient tombs.
</P>
<P>
Patrols have been set up in major villages to provide 24-hour
protection and, as a result, none of the tombs were broken into
last year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
