<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-13 09:58 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kurdish Official Blames Baghdad for </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, March 13 (Xinhua) -- A senior official of the
Patriotic Union of Kurdistan (PUK) in northern Iraq Blamed the
Iraqi government for an assassination in northern Iraq.
</P>
<P>
Local newspaper Daily News today quoted Fuad Masum, a member of
the PUK leadership, as saying that Baghdad wanted to make the
situation in northern Iraq more complicated.
</P>
<P>
Masum made the remarks following the killing of Muhiddin
Rahim, a high-ranking Kurdistan Democratic Party (KDP) official,
in the northern Iraqi town of Erbil, which led to a complete KDP
pull-out from the Ankara peace talks Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Representatives of the three rival parties, the KDP, PUK and
Turkmen Front, met here early Tuesday to discuss measures for
bringing peace and stability to the northern Iraqi region.
</P>
<P>
The Ankara peace process started after bitter clashes between
the KDP and PUK last September.
</P>
<P>
"In Erbil, Iraqi security officials have influence. Their
involvement (in the assassination) is really a big possibility,"
Masum said.
</P>
<P>
The KDP withdrew from the peace talks Tuesday to protest
against the assassination of Rahim, claiming that the PUK was
directly involved in this terrorist action.
</P>
<P>
However, the PUK denied its involvement.
</P>
<P>
Masum also disclosed that the KDP and Baghdad would soon
reach an agreement, which is in its final stage now.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, a senior diplomat monitoring the situation in the
region said that the KDP's withdrawal from the peace talks
indicated that the Kurdish group was distancing itself from the
U.S. initiative and getting closer to the Iraqi government.
</P>
<P>
The United States, Britain and Turkey, mediators of the
tripartite peace talks of rival parties in northern Iraq,
intensified efforts to save the process, which was aimed at
reestablishing peace in the region.
</P>
<P>
Robert Deutsch, U.S. State Department Director of Northern
Gulf Affairs, told reporters that they were investigating the
assassination. He said the Ankara peace process would continue
following his consultations with his Turkish counterparts.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a regular press briefing Wednesday, Turkish
Foreign Ministry deputy spokesman Sermet Atacanli said that Turkey
hoped the Ankara peace talks would continue as planned despite
this sad event.
</P>
<P>
The United States, Britain and Turkey chaired a series of
multilateral meetings in Ankara in a bid to work out a
peaceful solution to the problem in northern Iraq. 
</P>
</TEXT>
