<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-13 10:18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Netanyahu Vows to Go Ahead with Building Project </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, March 13 (Xinhua) -- Despite growing Palestinian
anger and mounting international pressure, Israeli Prime Minister
Binyamin Netanyahu has vowed to carry out the controversial Har
Homa construction plan in East Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
Upon his return from a two-day visit to Russia, Netanyahu told
Public Security Minister Avigdor Kahalani Wednesday night at the
Ben-Gurion Airport that he had decided that the Har Homa
construction would begin within next week, the state-run Israel
Radio reported today.
</P>
<P>
Legally speaking, the government is waiting for the
green-light from the High Court of Justice which is reviewing
several petitions filed by peace activists who oppose the Har
Homa project. But the court is expected to reject the petitions
as it has done so several times in the past.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu said that bowing to the pressure from the
Palestinian National Authority (PNA) would induce further
Palestinian demands on Israel's withdrawing to the 1967 borders
and allowing the return of Palestinian refugees.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu is to convene today the inner cabinet to discuss
the current crisis in relations with the PNA which has called an
international conference in Gaza Saturday to muster support.
</P>
<P>
Israel has strongly denounced the PNA's move to convene the
conference, which the United States, Russia, European Union and
some Arab countries have agreed to attend.
</P>
<P>
In a statement released late Wednesday, the Israeli government
said the meeting was a violation of the Oslo accords, which
stipulated that the two sides should resolve all differences
through direct negotiations before seeking international
arbitration with the agreement of both sides.
</P>
<P>
The current crisis was caused by a series of recent Israeli
decisions on the further troop pullbacks on the West Bank, the
plan to build new settlement of 6,500 apartments in Har Homa of
East Jerusalem and the order to close four Palestinian offices in
the controversial city.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinian side is demanding the Israelis to hand over
more land in every stage of the three-phase pullbacks, to revoke
the Har Homa plan and not to close the offices.
</P>
<P>
In a move to avoid escalating the current tension, Kahalani
has decided not to close the four offices in East Jerusalem
which the police claimed were run by the PNA, the Israel Radio
said.
</P>
<P>
The four Palestinian offices are the Office for Small
Projects, the Committee for the Wounded, Welfare and Development
Committee and the Office of National Institutions.
</P>
<P>
Kahalani made the decision only after PNA lawyer Jawad
Boulos issued statements to him promising that the offices would
have nothing to do with the PNA.
</P>
<P>
Kahalani would hold consultations today with Attorney General
Elyakim Rubinstein on the legality of closing the offices and
make a final decision. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
