<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 0800 GMT, March 13 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW -- Visiting Israeli Prime Minister Binyamin Netanyahu
said Wednesday that relations between Israel and Russia has
reached a new level and the era of hostility is over.
</P>
<P>
"Russia and Israel have reached a new level of relations in
politics and economy," Netanyahu told a news conference before
ending his visit in Moscow. "They will be able to strengthen
friendship and mutual understanding."
</P>
<P>
He stressed that his visit will further promote bilateral
relations, especially in the economic field.
</P>
<P>
MOSCOW -- Russian President Boris Yeltsin has stopped many
formal activities and meetings to concentrate on studying
documents for the U.S.-Russian summit in Helsinki next week, the
President's press secretary said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Sergei Yastrzhembsky said NATO expansion, arms control and
Russian-U.S. relations would be the main items on the summit
agenda.
</P>
<P>
Yeltsin and his U.S. counterpart Bill Clinton will discuss
NATO's planned eastward expansion and Russia's stand on the plan,
he said.
</P>
<P>
The United States and its NATO allies will meet in Madrid in
July to decide which former Warsaw Pact nations will get the first
invitations to join NATO.
</P>
<P>
TIRANA -- Albanian President Sali Berisha Wednesday approved an
interim coalition government led by Prime Minister Bashkim Fino.
</P>
<P>
Fino, a leader of the main opposition Socialist Party, was
chosen as prime minister by Berisha Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The 15-member interim government was set up in a bid to end the
nearly two-week long unrest and to prepare for general elections
in June.
</P>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS -- The Palestine Liberation Organization on
Wednesday urged the General Assembly to denounce Israel's new
housing project in East Jerusalem and other actions that violated
U.N. resolutions.
</P>
<P>
Opening the debate in the 185-member assembly, PLO U.N.
observer Nasser al-Kidwa said Israel was aiming at "the
Judaization of occupied East Jerusalem and at changing its legal
status and its demographic composition," as well as at continuing
a "colonial settlement campaign" in the area it has occupied since
1967.
</P>
<P>
WASHINGTON -- The United States said on Wednesday that it
understood the feeling of Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat to call
for a international meeting in Gaza to voice his concerns over a
series of Israel's decisions, which were obviously violating
agreements reached by the Israelis and Palestinians over the past
years.
</P>
<P>
"This is an opportunity for the Palestinians to express their
concerns about the present situation in the Middle East and to
hear the views of friendly countries like the United States,"
State Department spokesman Nicholas Burns said at a news briefing.
</P>
<P>
Arafat called for the meeting following Israel's decisions to
build a Jewish neighborhood in historically Arab east Jerusalem,
to close four Palestinians offices in the same section of the holy
city and to pull out of the West Bank rural areas far less than
the Palestinians had expected.
</P>
<P>
The United States, the European Union, Japan, Norway and France
have been invited to attend the meeting scheduled to convene on
Saturday in Gaza. The State Department has announced that Edward
Abingdon, U.S. consul general in Jerusalem, will represent
Washington to attend the meeting. 
</P>
</TEXT>
