<HEADLINE> Foreign Businessmen Confident to Invest in China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 13 (Xinhua) -- Beijing-based Western businessmen
and bankers are confident that the economic goals China set for
1997 will not only benefit foreign enterprises which have come to
invest, but help the country itself to draw more investment from
overseas.
</P>
<P>
"I hold that the Chinese government is going in the right
direction with the economic plan proposed at the ongoing session
of the National People's Congress (NPC)," said Paul Portoff,
president of the Bayer China Ltd., one of the largest German
businesses in China.
</P>
<P>
In his government work report to the Fifth Session of the
Eighth NPC, China's legislature, Premier Li Peng said that the
Chinese government has set the goal for economic growth this year
at eight percent, and will try to keep price rises below 6.1
percent.
</P>
<P>
"I consider the premier's speech at the NPC very important. It
is an indicator of the three basic principles which will be
framing the direction for foreign investment over the next year
and a half," said American businessman Laurence Brahm, managing
director of the NAGA Group Ltd., an investment advisory group.
</P>
<P>
The three principles he listed include a careful and meticulous
review of the state-owned assets in connection with the approval
of each investment project, the protection of Chinese domestic
brands and brand names on the domestic market, and the
consideration of foreign brands' dominance on the Chinese market.
</P>
<P>
"From the perspective of investors, this should not be seen as
the measures of protection in nature. In fact, given the critical
transformation of the entire state-owned enterprise system which
will be expected to take place over the next 18 months, we have to
realize and accept this as a transitional period for the Chinese
economy," he said.
</P>
<P>
He acknowledged that multi-national businesses have come to
invest in China not because of its cheap labor, but because of the
potential huge market in the country.
</P>
<P>
"It is very correct that China is shifting its priority of
investment to infrastructure, agriculture and the central and
western provinces and regions," said Paul Portoff, adding that
foreign businesspeople investing in central and western China and
in sectors like agriculture would surely continue to receive the
support that investors had received in the coastal areas in the
early 1990s.
</P>
<P>
"In the next few years, Bayer company is expected to increase
its investment in China to 400 million US dollars from the current
160 million US dollars," he noted.
</P>
<P>
David Wang, chairman and GEO of GE (China) Co. Ltd., said the
Chinese government has succeeded in preventing the overheated
economy, and that the increase of foreign investment will also be
at the rate the government would like to see.
</P>
<P>
"We look at investments in China very positively in the future.
Our clients have been increasing their investments in China over
the last few years in infrastructure, including in the sectors of
telecommunications, power stations and forestry. I believe that
with China's new economic plan, these kind of companies should
have good future in China," said Anders Biorck, Beijing office
director of Kandinaviska Enskilda Banken, one of the largest banks
in northern Europe.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
