<HEADLINE> India's Software Exporters to Get Relief </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, March 13 (Xinhua) -- The government is planning to
introduce a package for software and electronics exporters in the
export- import policy for 1997-2002, which is to be announced next
month, commerce ministry sources said here today.
</P>
<P>
The changes are likely to be integrated into the chapter on
export-oriented units, which will be modified substantially.
</P>
<P>
The Commerce Ministry is considering several steps including
allowing software exporters to sell in the domestic market on-line
and allowing Internet connectivity for private electronic mail
providers, said the sources.
</P>
<P>
At present, exporters sell most of their software to clients
abroad on-line, but cannot use this channel for the domestic
market. Internet connectivity has been a long-standing demand of
private electronic mail providers and software companies.
</P>
<P>
Total software and hardware exports in 1995-96 were 2.6 billion
US dollars and are expected to cross 3 billion dollars in 1997-98,
the same sources said.  
</P>
