<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indian Government Prepares New Import Regime </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, March 13 (Xinhua) -- The Indian government has
prepared three major initiatives to prevent emergence of a foreign
exchange crisis with phased dismantling of quantitative
restrictions (QRS) on imports beginning from April 1, official
sources said here today.
</P>
<P>
The first initiative envisages imposing a surcharge exceeding
the import tariff already committed to the World Trade
Organization (WTO) for non-agricultural products. The government
gave the binding import duty rates in its offer under the Uruguay
round of talks on multilateral trade that concluded in December
1993.
</P>
<P>
The second initiative envisages dismantling of import licensing
and canalization of petroleum products at the end of QRS phase-out
schedule or even reworking the schedule if the balance of payments
(BOP) situation is critical.
</P>
<P>
The third step will be reimposing QRS in case the BOP situation
crosses the danger mark. Apart from this, the government will
reiterate its demand for imposition of higher binding tariff on
certain farm products such as milk and certain cereals which at
present attract zero or very low duty.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
