<HEADLINE> Governor Envisions Future Development of Thriving Province </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 13 (Xinhua) -- Guangdong Governor Lu Ruihua says
the south China province has made "remarkable progress" in
establishing a market economy and a new managerial mechanism for
state-owned enterprises and will maintain its lead in this regard.
</P>
<P>
The governor, who is here attending the National People's
Congress session, made the remark at a press conference here
today.
</P>
<P>
On Guangdong's future development, Lu said focus will be put on
boosting the efficiency of export-oriented light industrial
operations, and on the high and new technology sector.
</P>
<P>
He said the province targets a GDP growth of about ten percent
for this year.
</P>
<P>
Guangdong had a gross provincial product of close to 610
billion yuan last year, one sixth of China's total. In the same
year, the province had a foreign trade volume of 110 billion US
dollars and received actual overseas investment of 13.9 billion US
dollars, both ranking first in the country.
</P>
<P>
The governor added that Guangdong made steady progress last
year in reform of state-owned enterprises, and that the 70 major
enterprise groups which received priority government support last
year are playing a "pillar" role in the provincial economy.
</P>
<P>
He said reform of the 187 pilot enterprises aimed at
establishing a modern enterprise system will be accelerated.
</P>
<P>
Concerning poverty alleviation, Lu said that 400,000 people in
Guangdong were lifted out of absolute poverty last year and that
the provincial authorities are confident of basically lifting the
remaining 600,000 people out of poverty this year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
