<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-13 09:17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Former U.S. Commander Advocates for Kuwaiti </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, March 13 (Xinhua) -- A former U.S. military
commander involved in the 1991 Gulf War has advocated Kuwait
should rely on western military allies for its security in view
of its insufficient resources to defend itself.
</P>
<P>
This came in an exclusive interview given by John Yeosock,
deputy commanding general of the coalition forces in the Gulf War
to end Iraq's August 1990 invasion of Kuwait, with the local
English daily Arab Times, which was published today.
</P>
<P>
He said that "it is difficult for Kuwait to be militarily
self-reliant because of its small size, limited population and
the nature of the threats facing the country."
</P>
<P>
"I don't think it is reasonable or possible" for Kuwait to be
self-sufficient in defending its integrity, "simply because
Kuwait is not large enough to stand up to any adverse threat
from anywhere in the region," the former army commander added.
</P>
<P>
He asserted that it was important for Kuwait to retain a very
strong coalition with friendly nations, as it had been during the
Gulf War.
</P>
<P>
Yeosock arrived in Kuwait Monday to discuss defense
initiatives with the Kuwaiti Ministry of Defense, the National
Guard and the U. S. officials based in Kuwait.
</P>
<P>
Besides, the U.S. former military commander said what is of
"vital importance to Kuwait is to continue to nurture and foster
an armed force which is truly professional in all branches of
service. They have to continue to strive and incorporate the most
capable systems they are able to obtain."
</P>
<P>
Yeosock is currently an advisor to the U.S. Lockheed
Group company, Lockheed Martin Electronics and Missiles.
</P>
<P>
"Fundamentally, Kuwait should possess a force that can be
reinforced by its allies. For this they need capabilities and
systems similar to those possessed by friendly nations which
when integrated will provide even greater deterrence," he said.
</P>
<P>
On the purpose of his current visit to Kuwait, the official
told the newspaper that "I am here in the interests of Kuwait
since I have a very personal interest to try and assure that
they can get on with building a professional and capable armed
force."
</P>
<P>
"I know that American industry and business can assist,
nurture, enhance and bolster a more professional force in
Kuwait," he added.
</P>
<P>
Kuwait had earmarked 12 billion U.S. dollars right after the
Gulf War in 1991 to reconstruct and strengthen its military
forces in a 10-year period. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
