<HEADLINE> Mkapa Reiterates Non-Intervention Position in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, March 13 (Xinhua) -- Tanzanian President
Benjamin Mkapa has reiterated the Union govrnment's position of
not intervening in the Zanzibar political crisis, local press
reported today.
</P>
<P>
The reaffirmation followed renewed donor pressure urging that
the president initiate dialogue and action to resolve the
political impasse on the Isles.
</P>
<P>
Patrick Chokala, the Press Secretary to the president, said in
an interview here on Wednesday that there was nothing new that
the donors have stated in their new request.
</P>
<P>
"The donors have been backing the opposition against the Isles
government since the general elections on October 22, 1995 after
Salmin Amour of the Revolutionary Party (CCM) was proclaimed the
winner," he said.
</P>
<P>
"There is nothing new from the donor community on the Isles
political crisis and there is similarly nothing changed on the
side of the president," he said.
</P>
<P>
Chokala said the president had no mandate to change the Isles
general election results as preferred by donors and the
opposition.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the press secretary said members of the House of
Representatives from the opposition Civic United Front (CUF)
should attend House sessions where the matter can be resolved in
a proper manner.
</P>
<P>
He said President Mkapa was preoccupied with the opposition
boycott of House sessions because they were denying the people
the right of representation.
</P>
<P>
They were also denying the government their contribution to
policy making, he added.
</P>
<P>
"CUF must accept to compromise on major issues with the Isles
government in order to settle the election wrangle in a peaceful
manner," stressed the presidential press secretary.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, Hafidh Ally, a Zanzibar government spokesman said in
the town of Zanzibar that donor pressure on the Isles government
to meet CUF and find a solution to the crisis would not succeed.
</P>
<P>
He said the government of Salmin Amour was legitimate, an
authority put in place by majority consensus.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman ruled out acceptance of donor assistance
accompanied by political conditionalities.
</P>
<P>
According to a report, a development cooperation official of
the European Union reiterated early this week that donors would
not assist any programs in Zanzibar if the matter was not
resolved.
</P>
<P>
In the last general elections, President Amour was re-elected.
However, the opposition CUF refused to accept the poll result,
claiming the election was "rigged".  
</P>
</TEXT>
