<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sichuan's Couples Embrace "One Child" Policy (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHENGDU, March 13 (Xinhua) -- Jia Maolin, a 92-year-old farmer
in Sichuan, China's most populous province, raised 15 children
after getting married at 18, counting on his descendants to build
up family fortunes.
</P>
<P>
But, he lived in an abyss of misery for most of his life, and
his wife died of poverty and overwork many years ago.
</P>
<P>
His grandson, Jia Qingfu, doesn't want to tread old Jia's
beaten path. The 28-year-old man spent five years farming
livestock before he and his wife decided to have a child.
</P>
<P>
"My wife and I built a chicken farm that produces 1,000 kg of
eggs a day. We earn more than 30,000 yuan each year," Jia said.
</P>
<P>
"I think early birth keeps newly-weds from pursuing their
dreams in their prime," he said.
</P>
<P>
A recent survey showed that more than a million young couples
in Sichuan shared Jia's view. The majority of child-bearing
couples said they would have one child.
</P>
<P>
One young couple in Ping'an Township delayed having a child
until they saved 500,000 yuan from their restaurant business.
</P>
<P>
The wife, named Gan Zeqiong, gave birth to a baby girl on their
sixth wedding anniversary.
</P>
<P>
"We wanted to get rich before the child came. This way, we can
send her to the best school in China or maybe abroad when she
grows up," Gan said.
</P>
<P>
"Waiting to have children later benefits not only the family
but also the country," she added.
</P>
<P>
Sichuan, the most densely-populated province in China, has a
population of 110 million, of which, 90 million live in rural
areas. The dilemma of growing population and shrinking farmland
has hindered Sichuan's economic growth.
</P>
<P>
Since 1970s, the province began to practise family planning as
in other Chinese provinces, encouraging couples to limit
themselves to having one child.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970313.0199 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sichuan's Couples Embrace "One Child" Policy (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
As a result, Sichuan's population growth rate has dropped from
29.5 per thousand in 1970 to 17 per thousand in 1995. While the
per capita income of farmers rose to 1,900 yuan in 1996 from 187
yuan in 1980.
</P>
<P>
China has postponed hitting the 1.2 billion population mark for
nine years because of implementation of the "one child" policy.
</P>
<P>
The old idea of "the more children you have, the happier you
are" has given way to "having fewer but healthier births." Many
people would rather improve the quality of their lives than have
more children, said Xie Mingdao, a population expert.
</P>
<P>
In rural areas, one-child families are provided with government
loans and raw farm materials such as fertilizer and improved seed
strains and given opportunities to study modern agro-techniques.
</P>
<P>
China's social security programs assuage the fears of the
elderly that nobody will take care of them.
</P>
<P>
Luo Fenglan, an old woman in Baihe Village, said: "I can get a
monthly pension of 280 yuan when I come to the age of 60. That's
enough for me even if I have no support from my daughter."
</P>
<P>
Compelled by a fast-moving career-oriented lifestyle, young
urban couples voluntarily postpone marriage and pregnancy.
</P>
<P>
Chen Yu, a female post-graduate at the Sichuan Union University
said, early marriage and childrearing will cost me opportunities
to compete with my male partners."
</P>
<P>
Urban districts in China reflect a trend towards lower birth
rates, lower mortality, and lower population growth.
</P>
<P>
Peng Peiyun, a top official in charge of China's family
planning, believes the Chinese Government is capable of
controlling its population within 1.3 billion by the end of this
century. 
</P>
</TEXT>
