<HEADLINE> Law and Order, Priorities of Nepal's New Government </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, March 13 (Xinhua) -- Nepal's new coalition
government will give top priorities to maintaining law and order
and speeding up the country's economic development, Prime Minister
Lokendra Bahadur Chand said today.
</P>
<P>
Chand, whose eight-member cabinet took office Wednesday, told a
press conference here today that his government is committed to
facing and addressing the country's various problems like leftist
uprising, severe poverty and rampant corruption.
</P>
<P>
Answering a question, the prime minister said that his
government will go to the root of the ultra-leftist armed movement
under the name of "People's War" and try to solve the problem
through dialogue instead of suppression.
</P>
<P>
The anti-government movement, launched by an ultra-leftist
group one year ago, has so far claimed over 80 lives including
political activists, policemen and civilians by resorting to
activities like looting, killing and armed confrontation with
police, mostly in remote hilly areas.
</P>
<P>
The new government will also ensure steady economic development
of the country through maintaining clean and impartial
administration, Chand said in a statement issued at the press
conference.
</P>
<P>
Corruption control will be put on the list of priorities of the
three-party government, he said.
</P>
<P>
The government was formed by Chand's National Democratic Party
(RPP), the Communist Party of Nepal (United Marxist Leninist,
CPN-UML) and the Nepal Goodwill Party (NSP) to replace the former
government, which resigned last week after losing a confidence
vote in parliament.
</P>
<P>
The new cabinet is expected to announce a common policy
platform under an agreement of the three ruling partners in two or
three days, according to a cabinet member.
</P>
<P>
The Chand government will seek a vote of confidence in the
lower house of parliament within two weeks, sources said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
