<HEADLINE> Thai School Students Required for Drug Tests </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, March 13 (Xinhua) -- Thai students applying for
entrance into technical and vocational schools nationwide will be
required to pass a drug test, a senior Thai education official
said on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The new requirement will be applied in all state technical and
vocational schools this academic year to prevent drug abuses in
the schools, said Thong-yu Kaewsaiha, director-general of the
Vocation Education Department.
</P>
<P>
The new rule will be flexible to allow each technical college
to set their own criteria to turn down applicants, the official
was quoted as saying by local newspapers.
</P>
<P>
Drug users who are not chronically addicted may be permitted to
study under the close supervision of teachers and parents, he
added.
</P>
<P>
However, the official said, only 0.6 percent of some 206,000
students at state technical schools nationwide have a history of
drug abuse, stressing that the requirement is designed to help
ensure drugs do not become a major problem in the schools.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970313.0209 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bangladeshi PM Rules Out Relocation of Muslim Settlers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, March 13 (Xinhua) -- Bangladeshi Prime Minister Sheikh
Hasina Wednesday said Muslim settlers would not be relocated from
the Chittagong hill tracts (CHT), where the Chakma tribal rebels
have been seeking autonomy ever since 1973.
</P>
<P>
"We will neither force anyone to stay there or ask anyone to
leave any place," said Hasina in Chittagong city, who was taking
stock of the law and order situation in different districts of the
Chittagong division, particularly the three districts of the CHT.
</P>
<P>
She also directed the concerned authorities to take proper care
and steps for the repatriation of Chakma refugees from neighboring
India, beginning on March 28.
</P>
<P>
Her directive came at a time when the government is holding
talks with the tribal leaders in the capital Dhaka for a political
solution to the CHT problem.
</P>
<P>
The crucial fourth round of talks between the Chakma rebels and
the government of Sheikh Hasina began Wednesday and got bogged
down on the unresolved issues including the relocation of Muslim
settlers and land dispute.
</P>
<P>
The Buddhist rebels, who have been fighting a bush war in the
resource-rich hill districts, demanded removal of all Muslim
settlers from the plains.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, a dawn-to-dusk strike was observed in the three hill
districts of the CHT. Strike organizers protested what they called
"unilateral peace deal" with the tribal rebels and were strongly
against the removal of Muslim settlers in the CHT.  
</P>
</TEXT>
