<DOCNO> XIE19970313.0210 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-13 08:49 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lebanon Slashes Food Imports </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, March 13 (Xinhua) -- In a surprise move likely to
anger some of the country's trade partners, Lebanon's government
has decided to slash food imports dramatically in a drive to
prop up the agricultural sector and to activate local
industries.
</P>
<P>
Prime Minister Rafik Hariri was quoted today by the Daily
Star as saying that the Agricultural Ministry had been given a
maximum of one month to prepare a list of agricultural items
exempt from the ban, mainly because they were needed for local
industrial use.
</P>
<P>
But the flow of all other agricultural products which can be
home-grown will be strictly banned as of October 1 this year, the
prime minister said at the end of a cabinet meeting Wednesday
night.
</P>
<P>
Lebanon has angered Jordan and Egypt recently with amendments
to the food import calendar that effectively restricted the flow
of fruit and vegetables.
</P>
<P>
Amman and Cairo regarded the alterations as violations of
existing trade accords.
</P>
<P>
Hariri said it was time for his country to lower its
dependency on food imports.
</P>
<P>
Lebanon's current food imports bill averages 1.4 billion
U.S. dollars a year, and is considered a key reason for the
imbalance in foreign trade, the Beirut only English daily noted.
</P>
<P>
Hariri said some items which Lebanon remains unable to
produce in quantities to meet consumer demands, namely beans and
chickpeas, will be exempt from the ban.
</P>
<P>
But "classical products like tomatoes, potatoes, lettuce or
cucumbers, will be entirely home-grown," the billionaire prime
minister said.
</P>
<P>
He played down the impact the decision would have on the
country, which imported up to 80 percent of its food.
</P>
<P>
"Not too long ago we banned the import of bananas, and after
a very shot period of time, Lebanon turned from an importer of
banana to an exporter of the product," Hariri argued.
</P>
<P>
"We believe that these decisions will offer a great incentive
for people to cling to their land and will also help increase
agricultural production and reduce imports," Hariri said.
</P>
<P>
He disclosed that other measures to "encourage investment in
the agricultural sector across the country" were currently under
study and would soon be presented to parliament for
endorsement. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
