Capobianco faces the threat of a four-year world ban if he loses
his International Amateur Athletics Federation (IAAF) hearing
against drug allegations this weekend in Monte Carlo.
</P>
<P>
The 26-year-old tested positive to the anabolic steroid
stanozolol at a track meet in the Netherlands in May last year,
but he was still allowed to race at the Atlanta Olympics after
being cleared by an independent tribunal namely Athletics
Australia (AA).
</P>
<P>
The IAAF, which claimed to have constructed a watertight case
against Capobianco late last year, refuted the outcome of the
Australian inquiry on reason of the lack of complete
evidence to the hearing.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, AA spokesman David Culbert said Thursday the AA
stood by its decision to clear Capobianco.
</P>
<P>
Capobianco, who has maintained the test result was caused by
faulty testing procedures, has indicated he would take his case
to the civil court system whatever the outcome in Monte
Carlo. 
