<HEADLINE> Uganda's Road Traffic Accidents Rise </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, March 13 (Xinhua) -- A total of 1,594 Ugandans died
in road accidents last year, a local newspaper, "the Crusader",
reported today.
</P>
<P>
It quoted the 1996 Traffic Offenses Report, released by the
police yesterday, as saying that the figure marked a 3.1 percent
increase in the number of fatalities on Ugandan roads from 1,546
deaths in 1995 when the grim harvest on the roads grew worse.
</P>
<P>
In 1994, 1,289 Ugandans perished in road accidents.
</P>
<P>
The report blamed poor driving, poor roads, lenient laws and
drunken driving as the major causes of road accidents.
</P>
<P>
Ugandan capital Kampala registered 289 accident deaths last
year, the highest among the cities in the country.
</P>
<P>
Uganda ranks second in Africa after Ethiopia in road traffic
accidents. According to 1995 statistics, Uganda had 161
fatalities per 10,000 vehicles followed by Ghana with 111
accidents while Ethiopia ranks first with 215 fatal accidents per
10,000 vehicles. 
</P>
</TEXT>
