<HEADLINE> Locusts Threaten Southern Africa </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, March 13 (Xinhua) -- The southern African region is
facing a serious threat of a locust invasion with continued heavy
rain.
</P>
<P>
The warning is from the control organization for eastern and
southern Africa of the International Red Locust Organization.
</P>
<P>
The local press today quoted the organization's regional chief
Afete Gadabu as saying that the potential areas feared to be
affected stretch from Mozambique, Malawi's Lake Chilwa Plains and
Tanzania's Valley Ears which pose a threat to Zambia due to
proximity of the areas.
</P>
<P>
Gadabu said there is a serious possibility of locust breeding
in the area growing into destructive hoppers soon.
</P>
<P>
There are fears that depending on the wind direction in the
region, Mozambique's hoppers may head for Zambia.
</P>
<P>
Zambia was put on such an alert last year, which promoted the
control organization into conjunction with the Agriculture
Ministry to launch a spray campaign against the pest. 
</P>
</TEXT>
