<HEADLINE> Nepali Businessmen to Boycott Upcoming VAT Tax </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, March 13 (Xinhua) -- Businessmen and industrialists
in Nepal have decided to boycott a new value added tax regime
(VAT) which the tax authorities is determined to impose from the
coming 1997-98 fiscal year starting in July.
</P>
<P>
A resolution against the decision to enforce the VAT this year
was unanimously adopted here Wednesday at the conclusion of a
national meeting on the impacts of the new tax.
</P>
<P>
The meeting, participated by those representing business and
industrial sectors from across the country, discussed various
aspects of VAT and concluded that the hasty introduction of the
VAT tax might jeopardize the whole economic system.
</P>
<P>
The new tax system would raise prices of daily commodities and
widen the already large gap between the rich and poor in the
country if implemented without adequate preparations, participants
warned.
</P>
<P>
The meeting also formed a national committee to work out future
programs for trying to make the upcoming VAT system abolished.
</P>
<P>
Representatives from various business groups decided at the
meeting to defy the government's appeal to register all business
organizations under the VAT from April.
</P>
<P>
Nepal's former government decided to impose the VAT system this
year aimed at doubling the national revenue through curbing tax
evasion.
</P>
<P>
It is expected the new government, which took power Wednesday,
would continue its predecessor's VAT policy.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
