<HEADLINE> New Men's Downhill Course Planned for 1999 Worlds </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, March 12 (Xinhua) -- Plans for a downhill to be
carved out of Beaver Creek Resort in time for the 1999 world
championships on Vail Mountain were unveilled on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Former Olympic champion Bernhard Russi, the downhill technical
advisor for the International Ski Federation (FIS), is overseeing
the design and construction of the new "Birds of Prey" course, to
be used for the men's downhill.
</P>
<P>
"The goal for this downhill is to find a challenging course
that will identify the best skier in the world at the world
championships," said Russi. "The public on course and watching on
TV should feel the excitement and difficulty of our sport.
</P>
<P>
"I think we have done it with Birds of Prey."
</P>
<P>
The course is set high on the mountain with the start at an
elevation of 3,482-meters and will finish at the bottom of Red
Tail at 2,732 meters. Spectators will use lifts and shuttle buses
to reach the finish area.
</P>
<P>
The vertical drop of the course will be 750 meters with an
average gradient of 27 percent, increasing to 45 percent in
sections. Skiers should average about 100 kilometers per hour and
reach top speeds of 150 kph.
</P>
<P>
Organisers plan to stage a World Cup downhill and a Super-G
test event in early December next season. 
</P>
</TEXT>
