<HEADLINE> NZ to Hold Referendum on Superannuation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WELLINGTON, March 13 (Xinhua) -- The New Zealand government has
introduced the legislation setting up details of a referendum on
compulsory superannuation, TVNZ reported today.
</P>
<P>
The referendum is to be held by postal ballot over three weeks
from September 5, and people will be asked "are you for or against
the retirement saving scheme."
</P>
<P>
The government said if a majority approve the proposal, it will
quickly move to introduce legislation to implement the scheme, the
report said.
</P>
<P>
Compulsory superannuation is conceived by the New Zealand First
party to replace the present practice of universal superannuation.
Under the scheme, all New Zealanders will have to set aside part
of their earnings as superannuation before the age of retirement.
</P>
<P>
Although the other major parties all oppose the scheme, the
holding of a referendum is contained in the coalition agreement
signed between the National Party and New Zealand First when they
formed the new government last December.  
</P>
</TEXT>
