<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Scientists Weigh Neutron Star by Measuring X-Rays </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, March 12 (Xinhua) -- Scientists have found a way to
weigh a neutron star by measuring its flickering X-ray radiation,
confirming for the first time the existence of unstable orbits
close to a compact star.
</P>
<P>
Scientists did so by measuring X-rays emitted by materials
falling from an orbiting companion star into the neutron star's
innermost orbit and then into the neutron star itself, a
newsletter from Columbia University said.
</P>
<P>
"The team is the first to use the presence of the innermost
stable orbit, a unique prediction of Einstein's General
Relativity, to gauge the mass of a neutron star." the newsletter
says.
</P>
<P>
Neutron stars have masses similar to that of the sun but have
diameters of only a few kilometers. They are thought to consist
entirely of densely packed neutrons and other elementary particles.
</P>
<P>
"From the rate of the X-ray flickering, we can determine the
precise position of the innermost stable orbit and therefore the
mass of the neutron star," said Philip Kaaret, associate professor
at Columbia University and the leading researcher.
</P>
<P>
In the case of 4U 1636-536, a neutron star found in the Milky
Way galaxy, researchers found that the falling matter from a
companion star emits X-rays that flicker at up to 1171 times per
second.
</P>
<P>
With the help of Einstein's theory, researchers then calculated
the mass of the neutron star from the frequency of the X-ray
pulses. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970313.0226 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
