<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indonesia, Australia to Sign Maritime Treaty </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, March 13 (Xinhua) -- Indonesian Foreign Minister Ali
Alatas will leave for the west Australian city of Perth today to
sign a maritime boundary treaty with his Australian counterpart
Alexander Downer, Foreign Ministry spokesman Gaffar Fadyl said.
</P>
<P>
"The signing of the treaty constitutes or marks a significant
historic milestone in bilateral relations," Alatas said Wednesday
after meeting President Soeharto.
</P>
<P>
The treaty with Australia will cover the formation of an
exclusive economic zone (EEZ) and an agreement on several maritime
boundaries, said Gaffar.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman explained that the sea boundary agreement will
cover three areas, namely the continental shelf and the EEZ
between Java and Christmas island, and the EEZs in the Arafura Sea
and East Timor Sea.
</P>
<P>
The accord to be signed in Perth will not be the first maritime
boundary treaty between the two nations.
</P>
<P>
Indonesia signed a similar treaty with Australia on the
continental shelf in the western region of the Timor Sea in 1971,
while a treaty on the Timor gap was signed in 1989. 
</P>
</TEXT>
