<HEADLINE> Chen Lu Flies to World Championships with No Medal Bid </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEJING, March 13 (Xinhua) -- World silver-medalist Chen Lu left
Beijing with four more fellow Chinese skaters on Thursday to take
part in the World Figure Skating Championships in Lausanne,
Switzerland.
</P>
<P>
Chen, who won the gold medal at the 1995 worlds but finished
second last year, admitted she could hardly get a medal this
time. She will be joined by Du Yankun in the women's individual
event at the championships slated from March 16-20.
</P>
<P>
Though being regarded as one of the hot favorites for medals in
the upcoming tournament by her rivals, Chen did not expect any
medal due to her right foot injury, which had banned her from
training for a long time.
</P>
<P>
"It's almost impossible for me to defend my runner-up ," said
20-year-old Chen, who missed all tournaments since last world
championships including Asian championships in Beijing last
October.
</P>
<P>
"I just recovered and began my regular training for a month, so
I don't think to display satisfactory performance in Lausanne. I
will do my best but it will be nice for me to enter top six
places," Chen added.
</P>
<P>
The world championships also serves as a qualifing tournament
for the 1998 Olympic Winter Games in Nagano, Japan, with top 24
having direct access to the Olympics.
</P>
<P>
Other three members in the Chinese delegation are the men's
singles skater Guo Zhengxin and Shen Xue/Zhao Hongbo in the
doubles. They were squeezed out of the 24 places in respective
events last year.
</P>
<P>
"What they expect this time is to enter the 24 and qualify for
the Winter Olympics," said Guo Ruijiu, Secretary of the Chinese
Skating Association. 
</P>
