<BODY>
<HEADLINE> ASEAN Urged to Enhance Intra-ASEAN Trade </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, March 13 (Xinhua) -- Chairman of ASEAN economic
ministers meeting Hartarto has called for more intense intra-ASEAN
trade to help maintain the momentum of the region's high economic
growth.
</P>
<P>
Hartarto made the remarks at the first ASEAN business summit
Wednesday, an official at the meeting said today.
</P>
<P>
Intra-ASEAN trade had improved significantly over the last few
years but there were still many opportunities to enhance ASEAN
trade, Hartarto said.
</P>
<P>
according to the ASEAN Secretariat, intra-ASEAN exports of all
goods grew 19.7 percent to 68.8 billion US dollars last year from
57.4 billion US dollars in 1994.
</P>
<P>
Hartarto, who is also Indonesia's coordinating minister of
production and distribution, said Indonesia will be one of the
world's five biggest economies by 2019 when its current 25-year
development plan ends.
</P>
<P>
Indonesia had experienced growth of over 7 percent a year in
the first three years of the current 25-year development program,
he said.
</P>
<P>
"Indonesia will become one of the five biggest economies in the
world with a nominal gross domestic product of 2 trillion US
dollars based on purchasing power parity," Hartarto said.
</P>
<P>
he said Indonesia should have a per capita gross domestic
product of 3,800 US dollars by 2019.
</P>
<P>
Hartarto said the government was also planning a decline in
population growth to an annual growth rate of less than 0.9
percent by 2019.
</P>
<P>
Indonesia has 22 million people living below the poverty line
and the government has pledged to bring the number down to zero in
ten years.
</P>
<P>
The ASEAN chamber of commerce and industry (ASEAN CCI), the
organizer of the two-day ASEAN business summit which began
Wednesday, proposed ASEAN adopt a timetable to eradicate poverty
by 2020.
</P>
<P>
ASEAN (the Association of Southeast Asian Nations) groups
Brunei, Indonesia, Malaysia, the Philippines, Singapore, Thailand
and Vietnam.
</P>
<P>
The summit meeting, which is being attended by some 600
businessmen, including those from non-ASEAN countries, is aimed at
preparing "a map of journey" toward the global market. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
