<HEADLINE> Thailand Wants Academics to Chart ASEAN's Path </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, March 13 (Xinhua) -- Thailand wants a group of eminent
persons to chart ASEAN's path toward closer economic integration
beyond 2003 when the ASEAN free trade area (AFTA) takes effect,
according to Thai Commerce Minister Narongchai Akrasanee.
</P>
<P>
The proposal would be put to ASEAN economic ministers who are
scheduled to meet in Cebu, the Philippines, this month, Narongchai
was quoted today by local press as saying
</P>
<P>
It would be best for academics to prepare the plan, rather than
government representatives, as they would be neutral and have more
time, he said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
If the group was formed, he hoped it could complete its
recommendations in time for approval by the annual meeting of
ASEAN economic ministers in September. It could then go to ASEAN
leaders scheduled to meet informally in Kuala Lumpur in October.
</P>
<P>
Karen Kittisataporn, director-general of the Commerce
Ministry's business economics department, said ASEAN's eminent
persons would probably be asked to map out a direction for the
trade group between 2003 and 2020.
</P>
<P>
Thailand was looking for closer economic integration by
liberalizing trade in goods, services, intellectual property and
investment.
</P>
<P>
AFTA would reduce all tariffs on goods traded among its members
to 0-5 percent by 2003. The ASEAN investment area scheduled to be
in place in 2010 would create a better environment for investors
both within and outside the region. 
</P>
</TEXT>
