<HEADLINE> Colombia Hit by Forest Fires </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SANTAFE DE BOGOTA, March 12 (Xinhua) -- Rescue units and
firefighters throughout Colombia have been put on high alert as
forest fires raged in many parts of the country.
</P>
<P>
More than 250 forest fires broke out in the country in recent
months due to high temperatures, and at least eight provinces have
declared a state of emergency, the Institute of Hydrology,
Meteorology and Environmental Studies said.
</P>
<P>
The fires have destroyed vast areas of crops and are
threatening important wildlife and nature reserves, which
constitute the richest ecological systems in the western
hemisphere.
</P>
<P>
The hardest-hit central province of Santander has reported more
than 150 fires this year.
</P>
<P>
A gigantic fire broke out last Sunday in Guaca city,
Bucaramanga province, devastating a large area of crops. So far
2,500 hectares of forests have been burnt down in the province,
said the fire chief of Bucaramanga city, capital of the province.
</P>
<P>
The blaze is also threatening two neighboring cities, he added.
</P>
<P>
In the east-central province of Boyaca, a fire started on
Monday destroying some 50 hectares of young pine trees and
shrubs. It has raged out of control and is spreading to the slopes
of the eastern Cordillera mountain in Colombia. 
</P>
</TEXT>
