<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China to End Hospital Overcharges </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 13 (Xinhua) -- Chinese health authority plans to
carry out a nation-wide reform to halt hospital overcharges for
medicines and expensive, unnecessary physical examinations.
</P>
<P>
Hospitals will be prohibited from profiting by prescribing and
selling unnecessary medicine to patients or by conducting
unnecessary physical examinations, according to a report in
today's "China Daily".
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, they will be permitted to raise fees for some
technical services such as clinical consultations and surgery, the
report quoted Li Hongshan, an official with Ministry of Public
Health, as saying.
</P>
<P>
The reforms are meant to end the practices of a number of
hospitals that often over-prescribe medicine and frequently
conduct expensive physical examinations with new high-tech
equipment on patients in order to compensate for low prices and
fees charged for consultations and some sophisticated treatments
requiring special equipment, the report said.
</P>
<P>
"Due to lack of investment from government and cheap technical
medical services, hospitals have to prescribe and sell expensive
medicines to make profits," Shi Wenhai, a doctor of People's
Hospital in Shaanxi Province, said in an interview with Xinhua.
</P>
<P>
According to statistics, hospital income earned through
selling medicines has accounted for 50 to 80 percent of total
revenue of a hospital in some places, Shi said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
