<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Berisha Approves Interim Government in Albania </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TIRANA, March 12 (Xinhua) -- Albanian President Sali Berisha
today approved an interim coalition government led by Prime
Minister Bashkim Fino.
</P>
<P>
Fino, a leader of the main opposition Socialist Party, was
chosen as prime minister by Berisha on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The interim government was set up in a bid to end the nearly
two-week long unrest and to prepare for general elections in June.
</P>
<P>
The new government is composed of 20 members from nine
parties. Berisha's Democratic Party takes six posts and the main
opposition, the Socialist Party, has five.
</P>
<P>
The Interior Ministry goes to the hands of the Democratic Party
and the Defense Ministry and Finance Ministry are to be chaired by
Socialists. The new foreign minister, Arjau Starova, is from the
Union of Social Democrats.
</P>
<P>
The Balkan state was plunged to unrest more than 10 days ago in
the wake of the collapse of dozens of pyramid savings schemes in
which hundreds of thousands of Albanians were left penniless.
</P>
<P>
Berisha was blamed for allowing the schemes and was demanded to
resign.
</P>
<P>
The president was forced on Sunday to agree to form a coalition
government to oversee early general elections after violent
clashes swept the south.
</P>
<P>
Rebels, who have seized most part of the south, are still
insisting on the resignation of Berisha, who was re-elected for a
second five-year term by the Democrat-dominated parliament last
week.
</P>
<P>
Unrest still plagues the south. Armed gangs reportedly attacked
a hospital in Sarande overnight and shooting in Gjirokaster, from
where Fino comes, injured six people.
</P>
<P>
Besides the unrest in the south, anti-government rebels looted
weapons from a military base near Elbasan, 55 kilometers from
Tirana.
</P>
<P>
On Tuesday, some 300 people broke into the barracks in Bajram
Curri, about 200 kilometers northeast of Tirana, and looted
hundreds of assault rifles.
</P>
<P>
It is estimated that 150,000 assault rifles were looted from
barracks during last week's violence. Heavy weapons, such as tanks
and anti-aircraft guns, were also found in the hands of the
ordinary people.
</P>
<P>
About 40 people have been killed since clashes erupted more
than 10 days ago.
</P>
<P>
In view of the volatile situation in Albania, many countries
have decided to evacuate their citizens living in the country.
</P>
<P>
The United States today ordered a limited evacuation of its
government personnel and urged private American citizens to leave
the country.
</P>
<P>
Britain, France, Germany, Italy and the Netherlands have also
called on their citizens to leave. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970313.0247 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Susanti Advances in All-England Badminton </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, March 12 (Xinhua) -- Susi Susanti keeps her dream alive
of winning her fifth All-England Championships title in her last
appearance in the event before retirement as her top-seeded
Indonesian compatriot Mia Audina was bumped out on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The 17-year-old Olympic silver medallist's hope of becoming the
youngest All-England winner was crushed when she lost 6-11, 11-8,
11-5 in the second round to the unseeded Dai Yun of China.
Meantime, Susanti's title chances were considerably increased when
she advanced to the quarter-finals with two wins for the loss of
only five points in total.
</P>
<P>
Another seed, the former world junior champion from China, Wang
Chen, placed in the five to eight category, also went out. Her
straight games loss to South Korea's Ra Kyung-Min meant there are
surprisingly three South Koreans in the last eight as well as three
Chinese.
</P>
<P>
Four Chinese have qualified to the last eight in men's singles
competition which saw nine of the 16 seeds bidding their farewell.
</P>
<P>
The most noticable to go out was the second seed Commonwealth
champion Rashid Sidek of Malaysia, who led 6-2 in the second
game, but could not handle the powerful smashing of a revived
world champion, Heryanto Arbi of Indonesia, and was beaten 15-7,
15-8.
</P>
<P>
Earlier Arbi was struggling hard against the 20-year-old
Englishman Mark Constable and managed to survive a game down and
3-9 behind in the second to pull off a hard-earned 10-15, 15-10,
15-9 victory.
</P>
<P>
But another Indonesian big name, the former world champion Joko
Suprianto, did bow out, partly due to a heavily strapped thigh
strain.
</P>
<P>
Suprianto, who won his world title in this same arena four
years ago but also lost in the second round of the All-England
last year, was ousted by Japanese Open champion Peter Rasmussen
15-10, 15-3.
</P>
<P>
The young left-hander Dane had a tough time later when he
struggled to survive into next round with a win by 17-14 in the
final game against Sweden's Tomas Johansson. 
</P>
</TEXT>
