<DOCNO> XIE19970313.0250 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Belgium Still World's Diamond Trade Center </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, March 12 (Xinhua) -- Belgium's diamond trade is still
the world's biggest with a turnover which rose by one-third in
1996, the Diamond High Council (DHC) said on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Turnover jumped in value to 715.1 billion Belgian francs
(20.31 billion U.S. dollars) in 1996, a 34 percent rise if
calculated with francs but 31 percent if with dollars, the DHC
said.
</P>
<P>
Imports of rough diamonds soared by 37 percent in value, to
357.7 billion francs (10.16 billion dollars). The major suppliers
were Russia, Australia, Congo and Zaire.
</P>
<P>
Exports of polished diamonds rose by 32 percent in value to
357.4 billion francs (10.15 billion dollars), and the United
States remained the biggest market, followed by Hong Kong and
Japan.
</P>
<P>
The northern Belgian port city of Antwerp, now accounting for
56 percent of the world turnover, consolidated its position as the
world's biggest diamond trading center, the council added.
</P>
<P>
Antwerp, host to 1,200 diamond companies and 15,000 people in
the trade, now cuts and markets about half of the world's uncut or
polished gems. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
