<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Manila Enhances Economic Ties With South </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, March 13 (Xinhua) -- Economic and trade ties are
expected to boom between the Philippines and South Asia and the
Middle East in the coming years after Philippine President Fidel
Ramos paid a 10-day visit to five nations in the two regions.
</P>
<P>
Upon his return from Bahrain Wednesday, Ramos described as an
"astounding success" his five-nation tour which took him to India,
Bangladesh, Pakistan, Qatar and Bahrain.
</P>
<P>
He said the trip had advanced the frontiers of Philippine
economic diplomacy and established new bridgeheads in the
country's search for more markets.
</P>
<P>
During his visit, Ramos obtained assurances from the five
countries of their continuing support and cooperation with the
Philippines, especially in the area of trade and investment.
</P>
<P>
Leaders of the five countries also pledged to provide easier
access for Philippine-made products to their domestic markets to
close the trade gap between the Philippines and their countries.
</P>
<P>
Most of the five countries, especially the two oil-rich Middle
East states, have enjoyed a surplus in their trade with the
Philippines in recent years.
</P>
<P>
The Philippines, whose trade gap widened to more than 12
billion U.S. dollars last year, has sought to tap more export
markets outside its traditional trade markets including the U.S.
and Southeast Asia. Among other regions, South Asia and the Middle
East are viewed by the Philippines as potential export markets.
</P>
<P>
For this purpose, Ramos conducted his first major foreign trip
to the five countries with a large group of leading Philippine
businessmen.
</P>
<P>
As a major achievement of his visit, Ramos brought back seven
bilateral agreements to strengthen cooperation between the
Philippines and these countries in economy, trade, science and
technology.
</P>
<P>
Under the agreements, joint business councils will be
established between the Philippines and the five nations to
promote bilateral trade and investment.
</P>
<P>
India agreed to make joint efforts with Manila to double their
trade from the 1996 level of about 250 million U.S. dollars to 500
million dollars by the year 2000.
</P>
<P>
Bangladesh agreed to promote and protect investment by the
Philippine businessmen in the country while Pakistan promised to
help the Philippines in the peaceful use of atomic energy.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Pakistan, Bangladesh, Qatar and Bahrain pledged to
continue their support to the ongoing peace process in the
southern Philippines by taking an active part in the region's
economic development.
</P>
<P>
The four countries, all members of the Organization of Islamic
Conference (OIC), helped the Philippine government in forging a
peace agreement with the Moro National Liberation Front last
September.
</P>
<P>
The historic peace accord ended nearly three decades of bloody
confrontation in the southern Philippines and created a peaceful
environment for the development of the region's war-shattered
economy.
</P>
<P>
Ramos' visit also enhanced labor relations between the
Philippines and the Middle East countries.
</P>
<P>
The Philippines signed two labor agreements with Qatar and
Bahrain to protect the welfare and rights of close to 50,000
Filipino overseas workers there.
</P>
<P>
These agreements are the first of its kind to be concluded by
the Philippines and the Middle East countries which hire almost
one-third of the about 4.2 million contract Filipino overseas
workers.
</P>
<P>
Overseas workers have played an important role in the
development of the Philippine economy in recent years by sending
home billions of dollars of remittances each year.
</P>
<P>
But cases of abuse of Filipino workers by their employers
happened now and then in the Middle East countries. Some cases
even affected relations between the Philippines and these
countries. 
</P>
</TEXT>
