<HEADLINE> Sluggish Sheep Count Gets Government's Goat </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ULAN BATOR, March 12 (Xinhua) -- It's getting more difficult to
separate the sheep from the goats in Mongolia these days.
</P>
<P>
The ratio of goats to sheep in the country has soared from 1:3
to 2:3 over the last few years, as breeders have flocked to goat
rearing to cash in on higher prices on the lucrative international
cashmere market.
</P>
<P>
Production of cashmere in Mongolia nearly quadrupled between
1993 and 1995, rising from 121.5 metric tons in 1993 to 232 metric
tons in 1994 and 421 in 1995.
</P>
<P>
The number of goats has risen by 614,000, an annual rate of
11.7 percent over the last few years, while the number of sheep
has risen by just 113,600 over the same period to 13.5 million,
Serjhuu, an expert at the Mongolian State Statistics Bureau, was
quoted as saying in the People's Right newspaper.
</P>
<P>
Now Serjhuu is urging the government to take measures,
including tax breaks, to boost sheep rearing and slow down the
growth in the goat population to bring the ratio back into balance.
</P>
<P>
He says the sluggish growth in sheep numbers could hit supplies
of mutton, a staple food in Mongolia.
</P>
<P>
Serjhuu also warned that it could also lead to a shortage of
wool as well as sheepskin for relevant industries. 
</P>
</TEXT>
