<HEADLINE> Presidium of NPC Session Holds Third Meeting </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 13 (Xinhua) -- The Presidium of the Fifth
Session of the Eighth National People's Congress (NPC) decided at
its third meeting today to put several draft laws and resolutions
to a vote at the last plenum of the session due on Friday.
</P>
<P>
Presided over by Qiao Shi, Chairman of the NPC Standing
Committee, the meeting first passed a draft resolution on the
method of number allocation and election for deputies to the Ninth
NPC, and decided to submit it to the plenary meeting for
deliberation.
</P>
<P>
It also passed a report by Xue Ju, Chairman of the NPC Law
Committee, on the results of deliberations on draft amendments to
the Criminal Law, on a draft national defense law, and on a draft method
for the election of deputies from the Hong Kong Special
Administrative Region (HKSAR) to the Ninth NPC.
</P>
<P>
Xue said that the three drafts had been deliberated on by all
delegations to the current NPC session, and that the legislators
held that these draft laws and method are generally feasible and
should be adopted at the current session after some revision.
</P>
<P>
"The Law Committee has revised the three drafts in accordance
with the lawmakers' opinions put forth during their
deliberations," he added.
</P>
<P>
The meeting decided by vote to submit the three drafts to the
plenum for approval.
</P>
<P>
It also passed and decided to put to a vote at the plenum a
draft decision on elevating Chongqing to the status of a
centrally-administered municipality, and draft resolutions on the
work report of the NPC Standing Committee, the work reports of the
Supreme People's Court and the Supreme People's Procuratorate, a
report on the inspection of the enforcement of the Agriculture
Law, and the work report of the NPC's Preparatory Committee for the
HKSAR.
</P>
<P>
The meeting passed a report about decisions on handling the
motions of the legislators attending the current NPC session made
by Cao Zhi, Secretary-General of the NPC Standing Committee and
Vice Secretary-General of the current session.
</P>
<P>
The session has received a total of 700 motions, of which 32
have come from delegations and each of the rest has been jointly
submitted by more than 30 legislators.
</P>
<P>
"These motions have taken Deng Xiaoping's theory of building
socialism with Chinese characteristics as the guideline, adhered
to the Party's basic line and principles, focused on the
implementation of the Ninth Five-Year Plan (1996-2000) and the
outline for long-range objectives for the year 2010, and put
forward a lot of important suggestions and ideas for deepening
reforms, opening wider to the outside world, and seeking a steady
progress," Cao noted.
</P>
<P>
He added that these motions cover a wide range of topics, which
include promoting shifts in the economic structure and the mode of
economic growth, establishing a socialist market economic
structure, improving the performance of large and medium-sized
state enterprises, strengthening agriculture, setting up a social
security system, developing science, technology, education and
culture, promoting socialist ethical-cultural progress, and
building democracy and a legal system. 
</P>
</TEXT>
