<HEADLINE> China's Exports to EU Rises to $19.83 Billion </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 13 (Xinhua) -- China's trade with the European
Union (EU) hit some 40 billion US dollars last year, with Chinese
exports rising 3.8 percent from a year ago to reach 19.83 billion
US dollars, today's "China Daily" reported.
</P>
<P>
China's growing market demand this year will help increase the
country's imports from EU, compared with the volume last year
which fell 6.5 percent from the year of 1995 to 19.87 billion US
dollars.
</P>
<P>
The bilateral trade last year fell 1.6 percent from 1995,
according to a recent report from the General Customs
Administration.
</P>
<P>
Sino-EU trade in 1996 was handled primarily between China's
seven coastal cities or provinces and eight EU members.
</P>
<P>
China mainly exported light industrial and textile products,
home appliances for machines, electronic products and precision
instruments.
</P>
<P>
Almost 90 percent of the goods China sold to EU last year were
mostly garments, footwear, textiles, luggage and toys. Garments
accounted for almost 12.3 percent of the total Chinese exports to
EU, and machines and electronics products took about 37 percent.
</P>
<P>
Imported manufactured goods formed 94.8 percent of all Chinese
imports from EU last year. Among them, textile machinery is the
largest import category last year, valued at 960 million US
dollars and rising 6.3 percent from the year of 1995. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
