<HEADLINE> East-West Cooperation in Developing Township Industries </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 13 (Xinhua) -- The last couple of years have
seen a sharp increase in the number of rural enterprises set up
jointly by China's coastal and central-western regions.
</P>
<P>
According to deputies attending the on-going session of the
National People's Congress (NPC), the number of township-run
industrial projects established jointly by coastal and interior
areas had reached 30,000 by the end of 1996, with 2,500 of them
set up in 1996 alone.
</P>
<P>
These projects involve 30 billion yuan in investment, said Guo
Jianping, head of the Township Administration Bureau of Shaoshan
City, Central China's Hunan Province.
</P>
<P>
"Though we have lagged behind in township industries and rural
development, we can learn from the east and develop our township
industries," said Guo.
</P>
<P>
He said enterprises in interior areas will pay greater
attention than before to making distinctive products of better
quality as well as to exploring rural markets.
</P>
<P>
"Rural industries should seek development through technological
advances rather than launching highly polluting projects," he
said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
