<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Seven Hundred Motions Put Forward during NPC Session </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 13 (Xinhua) -- A total of 700 motions have been
put forward during the current session of the National People's
Congress (NPC), the Chinese legislature, which started on March 1.
</P>
<P>
Among the motions, 32 have been put forth by NPC delegations,
and each of the remaining 668 was jointly sponsored by over 30
deputies, said Cao Zhi, secretary general of the NPC Standing
Committee, at the third meeting of the presidium of the Fifth
Session of the Eighth NPC today.
</P>
<P>
Guided by Deng Xiaoping's theory of building socialism with
Chinese characteristics, adhering to the basic line and principles
of the Party, Cao said, the motions focus on implementation of the
Ninth Five-Year Plan (1996-2000) and the outline for long-range
goals for the year 2010.
</P>
<P>
The motions concern deepening reform and expanding opening-up,
seeking a steady economic growth, promoting changes in the
economic system and economic growth mode, building a socialist
market economy, improving management of large and medium-sized
state-owned enterprises, consolidating agriculture as the base of
the national economy, establishing a social security system,
developing science, technology, education and culture, and
advancing socialist cultural and ethical progress, and democracy
and the legal system.
</P>
<P>
One hundred and forty of these motions have been transferred to
NPC special committees which, after examinations, will raise
suggestions to the NPC Standing Committee on whether or not to put
them on the agenda of the NPC or its Standing Committee.
</P>
<P>
Nine motions have been transferred to the Nationalities
Committee for examination, 32 to the Law Committee, eight to the
Committee for Internal and Judicial Affairs, 42 to the Financial
and Economic Committee, 32 to the Education, Science, Culture and
Public Health Committee, one to the Foreign Affairs Committee,
three to the Overseas Chinese Affairs Committee, and 13 to the
Committee for Environment and Resources Protection.
</P>
<P>
The remaining 560 motions will be turned over, as proposals or
critical opinions, to relevant government departments and
organizations, which will be responsible of offering replies.
</P>
<P>
In addition, by March 12, the secretariat of the session had
received 1,289 proposals, views and critical opinions from the
deputies. They will also be turned over to relevant government
departments and organizations, which have the obligation to give
replies. 
</P>
</TEXT>
