<HEADLINE> Mexico, Brazil Sign Accord on Space Center </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MEXICO CITY, March 12 (Xinhua) -- Mexico and Brazil have signed
an agreement to set up an education center for space technology
and science to promote international cooperation in the peaceful
use of outer space.
</P>
<P>
Mexico's ambassador to Brazil, Jose Luis Reyna, and Brazilian
science and technology minister, Israel Vargas, signed the
agreement in Brasilia, a press release by the Mexican Foreign
Ministry said.
</P>
<P>
The agreement was the culmination of six years of negotiations.
</P>
<P>
In 1991, Mexico and Brazil were designated by the United
Nations to set up a regional education center for space technology
and science in Latin America and the Caribbean.
</P>
<P>
Similar calls were also made in Asia-Pacific and Africa. The
U.N. hoped the regional centers would promote international
cooperation in the development of space technology. 
</P>
</TEXT>
