<HEADLINE> Ramos Denies Calling for Changes to Charter </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, March 13 (Xinhua) -- Philippine President Fidel Ramos
has denied calling for 97 or any number of amendments to the
Constitution, saying it was not his idea at all.
</P>
<P>
Ramos said upon his arrival Wednesday from a 10-day visit to
South Asia and the Middle East that the 97 changes to the
Constitution was not proposed by him but by a "constitutional
study group", local press reported today.
</P>
<P>
The President was reported earlier to favor at least 97
amendments to the Constitution to prepare the country for the 21st
century.
</P>
<P>
"We have listed 97 necessary amendments, considering that we
must modernize, that we must leapfrog, that we must pole-vault
into the 21st century", Ramos was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
While denying it was his idea, Ramos, however, said that it was
the people's right to be heard on Constitutional amendments.
</P>
<P>
"As somebody rightfully said, the Constitution does not own the
people. It is the people who own the Constitution," he said.
</P>
<P>
On the same day, Ramos also once more declared that he was
against moves to have his term extended beyond 1998, adding that
he hoped the people would not create a new issue out of the
extension of his power.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
