<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970313.0270 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Stability, Development Feature China's March Toward New Century (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Deputy Wu Shuqing, an economist, said: "Such a success is
unprecedented in China and has rarely happened elsewhere in the
world, and this indicates that the central authorities have become
more mature in exercising macro-controls."
</P>
<P>
To ensure a healthy development of the overall economy, China
has also formulated important strategies for further consolidating
agriculture and promoting a balanced economic development among
all regions.
</P>
<P>
Such strategies conform with the policy of grain safety for
China, which has a population of more than 1.2 billion, and
benefit the stability of rural areas where 800 million people
live.
</P>
<P>
They are also of important significance for preventing the
economic gap between eastern and western regions from widening.
</P>
<P>
As China has a huge domestic market potential, fears for a
slowdown in economic growth in the near future are not justified.
</P>
<P>
However, the state-owned economic sector suffering from low
efficiency faces tougher competition from non-stated-owned economic
sectors unleased by reforms. This has caused concern among people
of all social strata.
</P>
<P>
China has over the past three years basically set up the
framework of a macroeconomic control system compatible with market
economics and has meanwhile searched for a way to get state-owned
enterprises out of difficulty.
</P>
<P>
And a strategic thinking of attaching great importance to
rejuvenating big state-owned firms while giving greater freedom to
smaller ones and of speeding up structural readjustment has
gradually taken shape.
</P>
<P>
The NPC deputies noted that the strategy has been turned into
concrete policy measures in Premier Li Peng's report on the work
of the government. The report also reflects the market law of
survival for the fittest.
</P>
<P>
The deputies said they are optimistic about the prospect of
state-owned enterprises.
</P>
<P>
Economist Huang Da said: "If the established thinking is
closely followed, the ultimate solution of contradictions is only
a matter of time."
</P>
<P>
Lu Xueyi, a sociologist, perceived China's current tasks
from another angle.
</P>
<P>
It is inevitable that conflicts among various established
interests would exacerbate in the process of great changes, he
said, adding that similar experiences were reported in Western
developed countries when they moved from an agricultural society
to an industrial one.
</P>
<P>
From a sociological point of view, China's reform is a
reshuffling of established interests, Lu said.
</P>
<P>
As a matter of fact, though there exist contradictions among
regional interests, the overall objectives and corresponding
policies adopted by the central authorities have won support from
the overwhelming majority. The reason is that policy-makers have
always followed one same standard, namely, that polices should be
conducive to the development of productive forces, to boosting the
overall national strength, and to improving people's living
standard. The three "conducive's," in fact, are regarded as the
essence of Deng Xiaoping's theory of building socialism with
Chinese characteristics. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970313.0271 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Two Austrian Airlines to Be Merged </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
VIENNA, March 12 (Xinhua) -- Austria's state-own airline, AUA,
has virtually acquired the country's private airline, Lauda, by
becoming the latter's biggest shareholder.
</P>
<P>
Rudolf Streicher, Chairman of AUA's Board of Supervisors,
announced at a press conference tonight that his company has
bought 36 percent of Lauda's basic stocks which carry voting
rights.
</P>
<P>
As a result, Lauda shares held by its founder Niki Lauda have
fallen from 39.7 percent to 30 percent, while those owned by
German airline, Lufthansa, dropped from 39.7 percent to 20
percent. Other shareholders kept the remaining 14 percent.
</P>
<P>
Niki Lauda will remain as the general manager of his company,
said Streicher.
</P>
<P>
The deal will take effect on June 1 after being ratified by
competent authorities. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
