<HEADLINE> Johansson Beats Volkov in Copenhagen Tennis </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
STOCKHOLM, March 12 (Xinhua) -- Thomas Johansson of Sweden beat
Russia's Alexander Volkov 4-6, 6-3, 6-2 on Wednesday to become the
first player to reach the quarterfinals of the Copenhagen Open
tennis tournament.
</P>
<P>
Johansson will play Jan Kroslak of Slovakia in the
quarterfinals. Kroslak beat Sweden's Magnus Norman 4-6, 6-4, 6-2
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, organizers annouced the withdrawal of top-seeded
Arnaud Boetsch of France because of flu.
</P>
<P>
Boetsch was made the top seed only after Magnus Gustafsson of
Sweden withdrew shortly before the tournament with an injury.
</P>
<P>
The withdrawal forced organizers to replace Boetsch with lucky
loser and fellow Frenchman Gerard Solves, who then lost to South
African qualifier Kevin Ullyett 6-4, 7-5.
</P>
<P>
Ullyett had beaten Solves in the qualification tournament.
Ullyet next plays another qualifier, Lars Burgsmuller of Germany.
</P>
<P>
In other singles action Thomas Carbonell of Spain whipped Eyal
Erlich of Israel 6-2, 6-2 while sixth-seed Karol Kucera of
Slovakia defeated Fabrice Santoro of France 6-1, 4-6, 6-1. Also,
Fredrik Fetterlein of Denmark, who entered the tournament through
a wild card, upset eight-seed Daniel Vacek of the Czech Republic
6-2, 6-7 (3-7), 6-2.
</P>
<P>
In doubles action, the top-seed, Menno Oosting of the
Netherland and Libor Pimek of Belgium, defeated Italians Christian
Brandi and Filippo Messori 7-5, 6-3.
</P>
<P>
Also, Andrei Olhovskiy of Russia and Brett Steven of New
Zealand combined to defeat Dutch pair Tom Kempers and Tom Nijssen
7-5, 7-6 (7-2) while Guillaume Raoux and Fabrice Santori of France
overwhelmed Steven Noteboom and Fernon Wibier of the Netherlands
6-2, 3-6, 6-3. 
</P>
</TEXT>
