<HEADLINE> Iran, Czech to Further Promote Bilateral Ties </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PRAGUE, March 12 (Xinhua) -- Iran's Foreign Minister, Akbar
Velayati, said today his visit to the Czech Republic, the first
since he became foreign minister 15 years ago, would help promote
bilateral relations.
</P>
<P>
An advisor to Czech Prime Minister, Vaclav Klaus, said his
country would maintain and improve economic cooperation with Iran.
</P>
<P>
During his two-day visit to the Czech Republic, which ended
today, Velayati has held talks with his Czech counterpart, Josef
Zielenice, Klaus and Industry and Trade Minister Vladimir Dlouhy
on further development of bilateral ties.
</P>
<P>
In recent years, Czech-Iranian relations have developed. The
Czech Republic did not join the second round of economic sanctions
against Iran proposed by the United States in 1995.
</P>
<P>
In October, 1995, Dlouhy held talks with the Iranian side on
the joint construction of a large-scale power station.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, economic and trade cooperation between the two
countries developed rapidly, with the bilateral trade volume
amounting to 104 million U.S. dollars in 1996, increasing 60
percent over the previous year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
