<BODY>
<HEADLINE> World's Largest Mineral Water Source Discovered In Brazil </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
RIO DE JANEIRO, March 12 (Xinhua) -- A Brazilian mining
geologist announced today that he has discovered a spring of
mineral water which has the highest flow in the world.
</P>
<P>
The spring is in the Curral Mountains, about 25 kilometers from
Belo Horizonte, capital of the state of Mina Gerais.
</P>
<P>
Geologist Hugo Steiner said the source has an extraction
capacity of 12 million liters per day, or 180 liters per second,
the largest in the world.
</P>
<P>
"This water costs nothing. It is excellent for drinking and
therefore of a high commercial value," said the 53 year-old
geologist, who has been prospecting in the area since 1981.
</P>
<P>
Steiner said the present biggest source of mineral water in the
world was in Poland, and it had an extraction capacity of 9.8
million liters per day. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970313.0276 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Boris Yeltsin Preparing for U.S.-Russian Summit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, March 12 (Xinhua) -- Russian President Boris Yeltsin
has stopped many formal activities and meetings to concentrate on
studying documents for the U.S.-Russian summit in Helsinki next
week, the President's press secretary said today.
</P>
<P>
Sergei Yastrzhembsky said NATO expansion, arms control and
Russian-U.S. relations would be the main items on the summit
agenda.
</P>
<P>
Yeltsin and his U.S. counterpart Bill Clinton will discuss
NATO's planned eastward expansion and Russia's stand on the plan,
he said.
</P>
<P>
The United States and its NATO allies will meet in Madrid in
July to decide which former Warsaw Pact nations will get the first
invitations to join NATO.
</P>
<P>
The Kremlin has repeatedly made its opposition clear and warned
that bringing its neighbors into the military alliance would
threaten Russia's security.
</P>
<P>
But Clinton is aiming to convince Yeltsin that NATO's expansion
will stabilize Europe and pose no threat to Russia.
</P>
<P>
Yeltsin and Clinton will also discuss arms control questions
such as how to interpret a 25-year-old anti-ballistic missile
(ABM) treaty and what follow-on limits on strategic nuclear
weapons should be put on the negotiating table, Yastrzhembsky said.
</P>
<P>
Russian-U.S. economic, finance and investment relations will
also be on the agenda. Yastrzhembsky said that although there had
been some progress in cooperation, there were still problems that
needed to be addressed. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
