<HEADLINE> Major News Items In Leading Australian Newspapers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, March 13 (Xinhua) -- The following are the major news
items in leading Australian newspapers today:
</P>
<P>
The Australian
</P>
<P>
-- Economic growth would need to accelerate from about 3.5
percent to between 4 and 4.5 percent before the jobless rate could
be substantially reduced, Prime Minister John Howard admitted
yesterday. With annual growth forecast stay at 3 to 3.5 percent
until the turn of the century, Howard's comments suggest
unemployment rate to stay about 8.5 percent well into the future.
</P>
<P>
The Age
</P>
<P>
-- The Federal Government is seeking urgent advice on the
legality of its proposed surcharge on superannuation amid warnings
that tens of thousands of people will abandon funds if the plan
goes ahead.
</P>
<P>
The Australian Financial Review
</P>
<P>
-- A major confrontation between the Federal Government and
business has been sparked by the 1.5 billion Australian dollars
(1.18 billion US dollars) superannuation surcharge, after Prime
Minister John Howard launched a stinging attack on the super
industry yesterday.  
</P>
</TEXT>
