<HEADLINE> Sampras Crashed to Ulihrach at Champions Cup Tennis </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, March 12 (Xinhua) -- World number one Pete Sampras
suffered his first defeat of 1997 when he was crashed by Bohdan
Ulihrach of the Czech Republic at the Champions Cup in Indian
Wells on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Sampras, who took a 17-0 1997 match record into the
second-round encounter, was ousted 7-6 (7-5), 7-5 by the
43rd-ranked Ulihrach.
</P>
<P>
The top seed had won his last four tournaments, including the
Australian Open in January, and was victorious in his previous 34
hardcourt matches, dating back to last August in Cincinnati.
</P>
<P>
Shortly after Sampras's shocking defeat, fourth seed Goran
Ivanisevic followed the top seed out the door.
</P>
<P>
The big-serving Croatian was bounced 7-5, 6-3 by American
doubles specialist Jonathan Stark, who was named to the U.S.
Davis Cup team earlier in the day.
</P>
<P>
Sixth seed Thomas Enqvist of Sweden, the last player to beat
Sampras on a hard court before Wednesday, also joined the casualty
list, falling 6-4, 6-4 to American Chris Woodruff, a semifinalist
last week at Scottsdale. 
</P>
</TEXT>
