<HEADLINE> Estonian Parliament Appoints New PM </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, March 12 (Xinhua) -- Estonia's parliament today
appointed Mart Siimaan prime minister of the Baltic republic,
replacing Tiit Vahi, who resigned over a real estate deal scandal
on February 13.
</P>
<P>
Siimaan, 50, was asked to form a new cabinet after the
parliament voted 72 to 13 for his election.
</P>
<P>
Under the law of Estonia, Siimaan will submit a name list of
the new government to President Lennart Meri for final approval
within a week.
</P>
<P>
He promised he would make little change to the Vahi government
and the policies of the former government would continue to be
carried out.
</P>
<P>
He said the new government would make efforts to push forward
reforms, stabilize the economy and reduce unemployment, so as to
join the European Union as soon as possible.
</P>
<P>
Siimaan, a former journalist, is president of the
parliamentary group of the main Coalition Party. 
</P>
</TEXT>
