<HEADLINE> Athens Ready for 2004 Olympics </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ATHENS, March 12 (Xinhua) -- A report released today by Athens
2004 Olympics Committee claims Athens of 2004 will be an idyll of
parklands free of traffic problems and air pollution.
</P>
<P>
The report, prepared by Greek and foreign scientists, said the
public works project currently underway will significantly improve
life quality of the Greek capital, in time for the 2004 Olympic
Games which Athens is compaigning to host.
</P>
<P>
The International Olympic Committee (IOC) has recently put
Athens alongside Rome as the frontrunners for the 2004 Olympics
destinations while indicating the city's suffocating air pollution
poses the greatest obstacle in the way of its bidding.
</P>
<P>
Last week IOC selected a shortlist of five cities, namely
Rome, Athens, Stockholm, Cape Town and Buenos Aires, to enter the
final bidding competition for the 2004 sports extravaganza.
</P>
<P>
The report has also drafted an action plan, with the
assistance of the country's Environment, Town Planning and Public
Works Ministry, to improve the capital's living standards and to
protect the environment, since the environmental factor plays a
potentially influential role in the selection.
</P>
<P>
In reply to the IOC assessment, the scientific report noted
that since 1990 smog levels in the city have shown a gradual
reducing trend and that the on-going public complex, which
embraces the metro subway system, the international airport at
Spata, a number of major road axes and industrial utility of
natural gas, would help further reduce the air and noises
pollution in the city.
</P>
<P>
And, the public works programme, revealed by the supervisor of
Athens 2004 action plan Kostas Liaskas, will furtherly cover the
construction of sports facilities, land use, transport, energy,
environmental management and other factors.
</P>
<P>
"In the year 2004, the Olympic Games will be held in a clean,
healthy and attractive Athens, which will be in the future a pole
of attraction for tourists and services, but will also meet the
desires of residents and the needs of production," he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
