<HEADLINE> Wiberg Wins Downhill, Goetschl Claims Season Title </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, March 12 (Xinhua) -- Overall champion Pernilla
Wiberg of Sweden wins her first downhill while Austrian Renate
Goetschl captured the downhill title at the World Cup Finals of
the Alpine skiing at Vail, Colorado, on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Wiberg, who became the first Scandinavian woman to win the
overall championship on the strength of four slalom and two
Super-G victories, roared down the 2,626-meter Vail Mountain
course in one minute, 43.28 seconds.
</P>
<P>
Goetschl, the 24th and last skier to race, successfully jumped
from third to first in the final downhill standings, won the title
by clocking 1:43.31 to tie German veteran Katja Seizinger for
second.
</P>
<P>
Goetschl leapfrogged over Swiss Heidi Zurbriggen, fifth in the
race, and Russian Warwara Zelenskaja, a dismal 18th, in the
standings to claim the season title.
</P>
<P>
Zurbriggen finished in 1:43.78 to finish behind fourth-placed
Italian Isolde Kostner in 1:43.61.
</P>
<P>
World downhill champion Hilary Lindh of the United States was
placed ninth in 1:44.15..
</P>
<P>
Goetschl, who won a downhill at Vail earlier this season,
finished with 483 points, Zurbriggen 466 points and Zelenskaja 423
points. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
