<DOCNO> XIE19970313.0304 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Fritz Strobl Wins Downhill at World Cup Alpine Skiing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, March 12 (Xinhua) -- Austrian Fritz Strobl ended
his first full World Cup season today as he outclassed the field
to win the men's downhill at the World Cup Finals of Alpine skiing
at Vail, Colorado.
</P>
<P>
Strobl, 24, streaked down the 2,704-meter course in one minute,
38.29 seconds to gain the victory on Vail Mountain.
</P>
<P>
As Strobl exulted after beating Italy's Kristian Ghedina and
Austrian Hannes Trinkl, French ace Luc Alphand frowned at failing
to fortify his lead in the overall standings after a sluggish
ninth-place finish.
</P>
<P>
Alphand, winner of three successive World Cup downhill titles,
was a full second slower than Strobl at 1:39.29 and picked up only
five points on overall rival Kjetil Andre Aamodt of Norway, who
finished 11th in the race.
</P>
<P>
Alphand now leads 1994 World Cup overall champion Aamodt by 122
points with three races left in the season.
</P>
<P>
Ghedina, who finished the season standings in second place
ahead of Strobl, was 0.37 of a second behind in 1:38.66 with
Trinkl just two-hundredths of a second slower.
</P>
<P>
Alphand is striving for an historic World Cup overall title. If
he can hold off Aamodt, the 31-year-old racer would become the
first Frenchman since Jean-Claude Killy to win the overall crown
and the first speed specialist ever to claim the coveted title.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970313.0305 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Canada Suspends Mission Operation in Nigeria </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, March 12 (Xinhua) -- The Canadian government today
announced the temporary suspension of operations at the Canadian
High Commission in Lagos, Nigeria, due to safety concerns.
</P>
<P>
However, the suspension does not mean that Canada has broken
off bilateral diplomatic relations with the African country, the
government noted.
</P>
<P>
"Canadian officials at the Higher Commission have not been
given the security assurances by the Nigerians that we are
guaranteed in the Vienna Convention," Foreign Affairs Minister
Lloyd Axworthy said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
"It is the desire of Canada that the Nigerian government ensure
that this matter be resolved quickly so that the High Commission
can resume normal operations as soon as possible," Axworthy said.
</P>
<P>
According to the statement, the Canadian High Commission in
Lagos has been without a security officer since December 1996 and
efforts by Canada to send a replacement have been blocked by the
failure of the Nigerian government to issue a visa for this
person.
</P>
<P>
Canada had no choice in this matter and the suspension of
operations had to be made, it said.
</P>
<P>
The statement also accused Nigerian officials of making
"unfounded allegations" that Canada has supported recent acts of
violence in Nigeria.
</P>
<P>
"The combination of these allegations with the hindering of our
normal staffing has made it impossible to conduct routine
activities in Lagos," it added.
</P>
<P>
After suspension, Canadian consular affairs in Nigeria will be
managed by the embassy of the United States, while other High
Commission activities, such as visa services, will be transferred
to the High Commission in Accra, Ghana.
</P>
<P>
Canada's acting High Commissioner and other Canadian officials
in Lagos have already returned home, according to the statement.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970313.0306 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> PLO Urges UN Assembly to Denounce Israeli Settlement </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, March 12 (Xinhua) -- The Palestine Liberation
Organization on Wednesday urged the General Assembly to denounce
Israel's new housing project in East Jerusalem and other actions
that violated U.N. resolutions.
</P>
<P>
Opening the debate in the 185-member assembly, PLO U.N.
observer Nasser al-Kidwa said Israel was aiming at "the
Judaization of occupied East Jerusalem and at changing its legal
status and its demographic composition," as well as at continuing
a "colonial settlement campaign" in the area it has occupied since
1967.
</P>
<P>
"All of these measures represent a flagrant violation of
international humanitarian law and relevant United Nations
resolutions and a breach of the agreements concluded within the
framework of the Middle East peace process," he said.
</P>
<P>
The United States on Friday vetoed a Security Council
resolution calling on Israel to abandon the project in Jabal Abu
Ghneim, East Jerusalem. This move forced Arab countries to raise
the issue in the General Assembly, where there is no veto.
</P>
<P>
Speakers in the assembly were also virtually unanimous in
criticizing Israel and a resolution similar to the vetoed council
draft was certain to be adopted by an overwhelming majority when
put to a vote, probably on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Chinese Deputy Permanent Representative to the United
Nations Wang Xuexian said the Chinese delegation is of the
view that recent move by the Israeli government is bound to set
serious obstacles to the Palestine-Israel peace process and be
detrimental to the Middle East peace process as a whole. He
urged Israel to call off its plan to build Jewish settlements in
East Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
"The question of Jerusalem should be settled by the parties
concerned through negotiations on the basis of the relevant U.N.
resolutions," he said.
</P>
<P>
"When final-status negotiations are soon to start, the parties
concerned should avoid any unilateral move contrary to this
approach, since it will only further complicate the question
instead of rendering any help to its proper settlement or to the
Middle East peace process," he noted. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
