<HEADLINE> New York Stocks Slide </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, March 12 (Xinhua) -- Stocks on Wall Street slid this
afternoon despite a report that raised hopes that the Federal
Reserve may not need to raise interest rates to keep inflation
under control.
</P>
<P>
The Dow Jones industrial average lost 45.79 points to 7,039.37,
having recovered from a loss of more than 74 points.
</P>
<P>
Declining issues outnumbered advancers by more than a 5-to-3
margin on the New York Stock Exchange, with NYSE volume totaling
483.12 million shares as against 491.33 million in the previous
session.
</P>
<P>
The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock list fell 7.08 to 804.26, and
the NYSE's composite index fell 3.52 to 423.54.
</P>
<P>
The Nasdaq composite index fell 12.62 to 1,304.14, and the
American Stock Exchange composite index fell 1.39 to 602.04.
</P>
<P>
The Federal Reserve released its Beige Book report on regional
economic conditions this afternoon. The report showed that the
more jobs have been created, but that the resulting competition
for workers hasn't led to marked wage increases -- a key force
behind inflation.
</P>
<P>
In the bond market, the yield on the 30-year Treasury bond
finally stood at 6.87 percent, higher than late Tuesday's 6.85
percent.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
