<DOCNO> XIE19970313.0309 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Says Gaza Meeting Appropriate </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, March 12 (Xinhua) -- The United States said on
Wednesday that it understood the feeling of Palestinian leader
Yasser Arafat to call for a international meeting in Gaza to voice
his concerns over a series of Israel's decision, which were
obviously violating agreements reached by the Israelis and
Palestinians over the past years.
</P>
<P>
"This is an opportunity for the Palestinians to express their
concerns about the present situation in the Middle East and to
hear the views of friendly countries like the United States,"
State Department spokesman Nicholas Burns said at a news briefing.
</P>
<P>
Arafat called for the meeting following Israel's decisions to
build a Jewish neighborhood in historically Arab east Jerusalem,
to close four Palestinians offices in the same section of the holy
city and to pull out of the West Bank rural areas far less than
the Palestinians had expected.
</P>
<P>
The United States, the European Union, Japan, Norway and France
have been invited to attend the meeting scheduled to convene on
Saturday in Gaza.
</P>
<P>
The State Department has announced that Edward Abingdon, U.S.
consul general in Jerusalem, will represent Washington to attend
the meeting.
</P>
<P>
Israel, worried that Arafat will use the meeting to assemble a
worldwide coalition to press the Jewish state into concessions,
was said unhappy over the U.S. participation and has tried to
dissuade Washington from attending the meeting.
</P>
<P>
But Burns said: "It's appropriate that we go."
</P>
<P>
But he said the United States "does not see this meeting as a
forum for decisions on the Middle East peace issues or as a
negotiating session."
</P>
<P>
Neither it view the meeting "as an alternative to the direct
negotiations between Israel and the Palestinians," he added.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970313.0310 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Dollar Gets Weaker Against Mark, Stronger </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, March 12 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. dollar fell sharply
against most European currencies Wednesday, hurt by a rally in the
mark and new evidence that reduced the possibility of higher
American interest rates.
</P>
<P>
But the dollar ended higher against the yen and hit the
strongest level against the pound in nearly five months.
</P>
<P>
The continuing speculation that the European Monetary Union
single-currency planned for 1999 could be postponed pushed the
German mark higher. In New York, the dollar settled at 1.6932
marks, down from 1.7044 marks Tuesday and its lowest level since
the end of February.
</P>
<P>
The dollar cost 122.34 yen, up from 121.81. The pound cost
1.5992 U.S. dollars, down from 1.6072 dollars and the weakest
level since mid-October.
</P>
<P>
Other late dollar rates in New York compared with late Tuesday:
1.4552 Swiss francs, down from 1.4718; 5.7100 French francs, down
from 5.7455; 1,687.50 Italian lira, down from 1,695.00; 1.3627
Canadian dollars, down from 1.3668.  
</P>
