<DOCNO> XIE19970313.0312 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> US Fed Report Shows Moderate Price Pressures </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, March 12 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. Federal Reserve (Fed)
said today there was little evidence of wage and price pressures
and the economy was expanding moderately.
</P>
<P>
In its closely-watched survey of economic conditions gathered
from its 12 district banks, the U.S. Fed said that regional
"economies continue to expand at a relatively moderate pace."
</P>
<P>
"Tight labor markets still dominate in almost all parts of the
country. Nevertheless, wage gains generally remain moderate," it
said. "Price pressures, such as those reported by most retail and
manufacturing contacts, appear to have been temperate."
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the survey cited improved retail sales from a year
ago in most districts and "high levels of manufacturing activity,
with only pockets of weakness."
</P>
<P>
The survey said residential real estate markets were strong,
with increased building activity, higher sales compared with a
year earlier and rising home prices.
</P>
<P>
It said that commercial real estate markets were "even
stronger" with mild winter weather boosting activity along the
East Coast.
</P>
<P>
The periodic Fed survey on its regional districts covered the
period from mid-January through March 3. The so-called Beige Book
report will be the major basis with which the U.S. will decide its
monetary policy in next policy-making meeting on March 25.
</P>
<P>
Some analysts said that the Fed will maintain its wait-and-see
attitude about engineering an interest rate increase in its next
meeting.
</P>
<P>
But most economists believe the U.S. central bank eventually
will raise short-term interest rates this year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
