<DOCNO> XIE19970313.0313 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> US Urges Americans Leave Albania (updated) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, March 12 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. administration today
ordered a limited evacuation of its government personnel out of
Albania, urging private American citizens to leave the country.
</P>
<P>
"In view of the concerns that we have about the security
situation in Albania, we are ordering a draw-down of non-essential
United States government personnel in Albania," said State
Department spokesman Nicholas Burns.
</P>
<P>
"This is a precautionary measure because of the instability in
the country," he told reporters at a news briefing here.
</P>
<P>
Burns said that some 160 U.S. government employees and their
dependents will depart Albania, leaving 17 U.S. diplomats in the
U.S. Embassy in the country.
</P>
<P>
Albanian President Sali Berisha and the opposition agreed last
week to form a broad-based coalition government and an early
election in the country.
</P>
<P>
However, the situation is reportedly going worse in the country
as the fighting is continuing in the South.
</P>
<P>
"The positive political steps taken by President Berisha...have
not yet succeeded in improving conditions in the country because
the insurgency continues," Burns noted.
</P>
<P>
He said that dependents and non-essential personnel of the U.S.
in Albania will leave in the coming days.
</P>
<P>
"In addition, we are advising American citizens to consider
departing Albania as soon as possible," the spokesman added.
</P>
<P>
"Americans who wish to travel to Albania should not do so.
Americans who currently live in Albania should leave," he said.
</P>
<P>
There are about 2,000 private Americans in Albania.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Burns said that his country welcomes the
appointment of Bashkin Fino as Albania's new prime minister by
Berisha.
</P>
<P>
"We do call upon the new government, and all opposition
forces, to establish a decent political dialogue that would
lead to a cessation of hostilities," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
