<DOCNO> XIE19970313.0314 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton Urges Parents to Tell Children About Drugs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, March 12 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Bill Clinton
today urged baby boomers who once tried drugs to drop the guilt
and tell their children about the dangers of drugs in an effort to
prevent children from drug abuse.
</P>
<P>
"I think this business about how baby boomers all feel too
guilt-ridden to talk to their children is the biggest load of
hooey I ever heard. They have a bigger responsibility to talk to
their children," Clinton told a group of young people at a White
House anti-drug session with children.
</P>
<P>
Clinton said he has had no problem telling his daughter,
Chelsea, about his own experimentation with Marijuana and neither
should any other baby boomer parent. Parents have an obligation to
talk to their children regardless of their own drug histories, he
said.
</P>
<P>
Clinton said he told his daughter, "When I was 22 years old in
England and I thought there were no consequences, I tried
marijuana a couple of times. But if I had known then what I know
now, I would not have done it. It hadn't bothered me to tell her
that she shouldn't make the same mistakes I did."
</P>
<P>
Clinton was part of a town hall discussion, "Straight Talk on
Drugs," aired on ABC Radio as part of the station's month-long
public service campaign on the issue to prevent young people from
abusing drugs.
</P>
<P>
Surveys and statistics show that drug abuse was on the rise
among the young people in the United States in the last couple of
years although the situation was improving among the adults.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
