<DOCNO> XIE19970313.0315 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Computer Service Founder Charged with Pornography </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, March 12 (Xinhua) -- The founder of the U.S. first
free community computer network service has been charged with
possessing child pornography, according to an Associated Press
report.
</P>
<P>
Thomas Grundner, 51, was charged with possessing books,
magazines, periodicals, films, videotapes and other items that
showed minors engaging in sexual conduct, the report quoted the
U.S. Attorney's office as saying.
</P>
<P>
If convicted, Grundner faces a maximum of five years in prison
and a fine of 250,000 U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
Grundner founded the free-net computer system, offering free
e-mail, Internet access and some local information, while he was
an assistant professor in the family medicine department at Case
Western Reserve Medical School.
</P>
<P>
His system began in 1984 as an electronic bulletin board for
computer users and became Cleveland Free-Net in 1986, the nation's
first and largest public computer network. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
