<HEADLINE> Zimbabwean, Mozambican Businessmen Meet </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MAPUTO, March 12 (Xinhua) -- Zimbabwean and Mozambican
businessmen started a two-day meeting here today to boost their
trade to a new high with the help of the two governments.
</P>
<P>
Abilio Alfino, the Vice Minister for Industry, Trade and
Tourism of Mozambique, said his country expects more investment
from neighboring Zimbabwe, the second largest trade partner of
Mozambique after South Africa.
</P>
<P>
There are plenty of opportunities for investment in Mozambique,
especially in the areas of agriculture, fishing, mining and
other industries, said Alfino.
</P>
<P>
All efforts on promoting the two countries' trade will
be welcomed, said Alfino, adding the meeting sponsored by the
Zimbabwean Commercial Chamber is an important step to enhance
the Zimbabwean-Mozambican trade ties.
</P>
<P>
Ubert Mpotu, the Vice Minister for Industry and Trade of
Zimbabwe, said the Zimbabwean government put a priority to the
promotion of trade relations with its neighbors, especially
Mozambique, whose Beira Port is an outlet to the sea for Zimbabwe.
</P>
<P>
Zimbabwe is willing to get more imports from Mozambique, said
Mpotu, accompanied by businessmen from 32 Zimbabwean companies
who arrived here Monday after ending visits to Mozambique's Tete
and Beira cities.
</P>
<P>
Zimbabwe's exports to Mozambique valued at 40.7 million U.S.
Dollars in 1995, up from 31.9 million Dollars in 1993.
</P>
<P>
Mozambique mainly exports cashew nuts, timber, mineral and
sea products to and imports farm machines, tobacco, motorcars and
construction materials from Zimbabwe. enditem

